Title: Puget Sound Salish basketmaker, circa 1900
Notes: Coast Salish peoples are a diverse group of Indigenous people of the Pacific Northwest who speak related languages and have some common cultural traditions. The Coast Salish grouping includes many different tribal groups, all with their own names for themselves and most with their own languages. Coast Salish peoples have lived in the Pacific Northwest since time immemorial and their traditional lands surround the Salish Sea, including part of the Olympic Peninsula, the coast of Puget Sound, the eastern side of Vancouver Island, and the southern coast of British Columbia.     The Coast Salish peoples of the Puget Sound region were famous for their coiled and twined baskets. Some of the baskets were so tightly made that they could hold water. In this photo taken around 1900, a Coast Salish basketmaker holds a split cedar root in her mouth, ready to work it into her basket.     Caption information source: "Coast Salish people & languages," Burke Museum, retrieved from https://www.burkemuseum.org/collections-and-research/culture/contemporary-culture/coast-salish-art/coast-salish-people.

Title: Makah boy rowing a canoe at Neah Bay, 1900
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     In this photo, a small Makah boy holds the oars of a large cedar canoe at Neah Bay. Makah children learned how to handle canoes at a young age. The Makah used their large canoes for long-distance travel, fishing, and for hunting whales.     Caption information source: Makah Tribe website at https://makah.com  Caption on image: Copyrighted 1900

Title: Woman with hop basket, circa 1900
Notes: From the late 1860s to the early 1890s, hop farming was an important activity in the valleys of the Puget Sound region, including Puyallup, White River, and Snoqualmie. Indigenous workers came from through the Pacific Northwest, Canada, and Alaska (but especially from regional tribes like the Puyallup, Snoqualmie, Muckleshoot, Duwamish, Sammamish, Lummi, and Nisqually) as a seasonal labor force to harvest these crops in last summer and early autumn.    These Indigenous workers gathered the cone-like fruit into handmade baskets, as shown in the photograph. Indigenous people used split cedar or spruce root to make this type of open-weave storage basket, traditionally used to store dried foods and household goods in the longhouses.    Caption information source: "Indigenous Hop Pickers in Western Washington" by Hans Zeiger, HistoryLink.org Essay 21295.

Title: Nellie Stimson’s basket collection, Seattle, circa 1900
Notes: At the turn of 19th to 20th centuries, Indigenous artists in the Pacific Northwest were making baskets and carvings specifically for the tourist trade and were experimenting with form and design. In Nellie (Mrs. Fred) Stimson’s Seattle home, baskets from the Pacific Northwest as well as from the Great Basin and Southwest were displayed in abundance.    Caption information source: "Northwest Coast Basketry," by Silvia Koros for the Burke Museum, retrieved from https://www.burkemuseum.org/static/baskets/Teachersguideforbasketry.htm.

Title: Portrait of Yaht-le-min's wife, circa 1900
Notes: This is a portrait of the wife of Yaht-le-min (called General Taylor by the settlers), a sub-chief of the S'Klallam. Her name is not known. She had her portrait taken with a traditional clam basket in front of a handmade cattail mat. She wears a crucifix pendant, a symbol of the Christian faith introduced by missionaries in the mid-1800s.     Caption information source: "Land and People and Lifestyle," by Jerry Gorsline for the Port Gamble S'Klallam Tribe, retrieved from https://www.pgst.nsn.us/tribal-enterprises/noo-kayet-development/35-top-level/land-and-people-and-lifestyle

Title: Makah whale hunters landing their canoe at Neah Bay, 1900
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     The Makah people of Washington's Olympic Peninsula hunted whales and other sea mammals from large seagoing canoes. The hunters harpooned the animals and kept them from sinking by attaching floats made from sealskin filled with air. These carved cedar dugouts traveled miles out into the open ocean for whale hunting as well as for fishing and trading trips. This image shows a group of hunters landing their canoe at Neah Bay. After photographing the building of the Great Northern Railway through the Cascades and working as a cartographer, Wilse turned to commercial photography in 1897. In 1900, Wilse left for a visit to Norway and never returned. (Carolyn J. Marr, "Anders Beer Wilse: Photographer of the Pacific Northwest and Norway."  Columbia 8, no. 4 (Summer 1994): 24-29.)

The float inside the canoe is made from inflated sealskin and was attached to the harpoon line when it was thrust at the whale. Title: Encampment of Indigenous people on Ballast Island at the Seattle waterfront, circa 1900
Notes: In 1865 the Board of Trustees of Seattle passed Ordinance No. 5 banning Indigenous people from living in the city unless they worked for a non-Indigenous resident and lived on their employer’s property. Despite this attempt to enforce separation between Indigenous people and the settlers, Seattle depended on Indigenous people. Settlers relied on Native people for domestic work and for trade of fish, shellfish, and baskets. Indigenous people from across the Pacific Northwest also harvested hops in agricultural areas to the south and east of Seattle.     Because they were excluded from the rest of the city, many Indigenous people stayed on Ballast Island, either when passing through, temporarily stopping, or living on the island year-round. Ballast Island was in the harbor at the foot of Washington Street and was created when sailing ships dumped their ballast in Elliott Bay in order to take on cargo. The only place close to Seattle’s business district where Indigenous people were allowed to live, Ballast Island lacked a source of fresh water or permanent structures. As the waterfront grew in the 1890s, Ballast Island was gradually covered and by the time the seawall was built in 1916, the island was almost completely gone and its Indigenous residents had again been displaced.     This image shows part of the encampment on Ballast Island around 1900. The coastal Native peoples adopted canvas tents in place of their native cattail mat shelters for traveling.    Caption information source: "Exile to Ballast Island," Duwamish Tribe, retrieved from https://www.duwamishtribe.org/exile-to-ballast-island  Caption information source: "Seattle Board of Trustees passes ordinance, calling for removal of Indians from the town, on February 7, 1865," by Jennifer Ott, HistoryLink essay #10979, retrieved from https://www.historylink.org/file/10979

Title: Indigenous family working in a hop field in western Washington, circa 1900.
Notes: From the late 1860s to the early 1890s, hop farming was an important activity in the valleys of the Puget Sound region, including Puyallup, White River, and Snoqualmie. Indigenous workers came from throughout the Pacific Northwest, Canada, and Alaska (but especially from regional tribes like the Puyallup, Snoqualmie, Muckleshoot, Duwamish, Sammamish, Lummi, and Nisqually) as a seasonal labor force to harvest these crops in late summer and early autumn. Often, whole families would work together and on occasion entire villages were emptied as people left for the hops harvest. Workers would use downtime to socialize with each other, weave baskets to sell, or fish for salmon.     These Indigenous workers gathered the cone-like fruit into handmade baskets, as shown in this photograph. Indigenous people used split cedar or spruce root to make this type of open-weave storage basket, traditionally used to store dried foods and household goods in the longhouses.    Caption information source: "Indigenous Hop Pickers in Western Washington" by Hans Zeiger, HistoryLink.org Essay 21295.

Title: White woman buying baskets from an Indigenous woman, Seattle, circa 1911
Notes: At the turn of 19th to 20th centuries, Indigenous artists in the Pacific Northwest were making baskets and carvings specifically for the tourist trade and were experimenting with form and design. In this photo, taken around 1911 outside a downtown Seattle store, a woman bends to ask a basket seller about her wares. The mats and baskets are Nuu-chah-nulth (formerly called Nootka) in style. Title: Quinault canoe and sightseers, Moclips, Washington, 1914
Notes: The Quinault are a Coast Salish people whose historic territory was the southwestern Olympic Peninsula. The current Quinault Indian Nation (QIN) has a reservation covering part of their historic lands. In addition to Quinault people, the QIN includes people from several neighboring tribes: Queets, Quileutes, Hohs, Chehalis, Chinook, and Cowlitz. Fishing, especially for salmon, is an important part of Quinault culture. Salmon spawn on the Quinault and Ozette rivers. After the fish laid and fertilized their eggs, Quinault fishers use a wide array of nets or traps to catch them. Historically, the Quinault also hunted whales, seals, and sea lions.     In this image taken near Moclips, a group of tourists watches a Quinault canoe paddle out from the shore. Starting in the early 20th century, oceanside resorts were established on the Pacific coast south of the Quinault reservation, where city residents could enjoy the healthy sea air and salt water.     Caption information source: "Quinault," by Justine E. James and Leilani A. Chubby, in "Native Peoples of the Olympic Peninsula: Who We Are," by the Olympic Peninsula Intertribal Cultural Advisory Committee, University of Oklahoma Press, 2002, p. 99-106.

Title: Hwehlchtid's house at Shilshole with canoe anchored offshore, circa 1905
Notes: In 1855, representatives of the Indigenous peoples of the area now known as Seattle, including the Duwamish and Suquamish, signed the Treaty of Point Elliott. As part of this treaty, many Indigenous people agreed to move in their tribal groups to reservations outside of the Seattle area, but some remained. In 1865 the Board of Trustees of Seattle passed Ordinance No. 5 banning Indigenous people from living in the city unless they worked for a non-Indigenous resident and lived on their employer’s property.     Hwehlchtid (called Salmon Bay Charlie by the settlers) of the Shilshole people lived on the southern shore of Salmon Bay, near present-day Ballard, which was then outside of Seattle. Hwehlchtid and his wife Chilohleet'sa (Madeline) remained in their traditional homeland long after others of their tribe had moved away. This photo, taken around 1905, shows their home at Shilshole with a canoe docked outside. Although the wood planks of the house were not hand-hewn as in older dwellings, the traditional smoke hole with its adjustable cover is visible.    Caption source information: "City of the Changers: Indigenous People and the Transformation of  Seattle’s Watersheds," by Coll Thrush, Pacific Historical Review, (2006) Vol. 75, No. 1, pages 89–117, Accessed at http://web.mit.edu/people/spirn/Public/Granite%20Garden%20Research/Urban%20Environmental%20History/Thrush%202006%20Indigenous%20People%20Seattle.pdf

Title: Fishing camp at Eagle Harbor on Bainbridge Island, circa 1905
Notes: Bainbridge Island had been inhabited by the Suquamish people before the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott. In the early 20th century, a group of Indigenous people from British Columbia set up a camp on Eagle Harbor, near what is now Waterfront Park in Winslow. They harvested clams and fish from Eagle Harbor and other nearby waters to sell to Seattle residents and also dried salmon to preserve it for later use. In this photo, taken at the camp, men and children stand near their plank houses and salmon drying racks. Salmon fishing was an important part of culture and subsistence for many Indigenous people groups surrounding the Salish Sea.

Title: William Shelton carving a story pole, circa 1920
Notes: William Shelton (1868-1938), named Wha-ceh-dub or Whah-kay-dub in his native language of Lushootseed, was a cultural leader of the Snohomish and expert woodworker. During his lifetime, Indigenous people were confined to live on reservations and their children were taken to boarding schools. These schools prohibited Indigenous customs or languages in an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous children and eradicate their culture. At the time, many people both white and Indigenous believed that Indigenous people and their cultural identities would eventually vanish completely.     William Shelton wanted to preserve his peoples’ stories and cultural values through art. Though totem poles were not traditionally made by the Indigenous peoples of Washington, he decided to adapt the form. He gathered stories from elders of multiple tribes in western Washington and began carving a 60-foot pole with figures that represented the stories. The pole also included figures called skla’letut which represent guardian spirits or supernatural powers and figures that Shelton remembered from his childhood on the Tulalip Reservation. He called the result a "story pole." His first story pole was carved in 1912 and installed in 1913 in front of the Tulalip Indian School. Over the rest of his life Shelton carved at least 16 additional large story poles for public display.     This image shows Shelton carving a story pole commissioned by the City of Everett. This pole was installed in 1923 and includes figures of an octopus, a man, and a frog.     Caption information source: "The carved legacy of Snohomish cultural leader William Shelton," by Christy Christodoulides, Burke Museum, retrieved from: https://www.burkemuseum.org/news/carved-legacy-snohomish-cultural-leader-william-shelton  Caption information source: "Shelton, William (1868-1938)," by Margaret Riddle, HistoryLink essay #8928, retrieved from: https://www.historylink.org/File/8928

Title: Two Yakama couples in traditional dress, Seattle, January 29, 1921
Notes: The Yakama (formerly spelled Yakima) people have lived in the Columbia River basin since time immemorial. During the winter, they lived in permanent villages built on the valley floor, where the climate was most temperate. Starting in spring, they traveled along the rivers and into the hills to gather food. Some gathered roots and berries, and others fished in rivers, especially the Columbia and the Yakima. In 1855, a confederation of 14 tribal groups signed the Yakama Nation Treaty with the United States and ceded most of their traditional lands, but reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. These groups were: Kah-miltpah, Palouse, Klickitat, See-ap-Cat, Klinquit, Sk-in-pah, Li-ay-was, Oche-Chotes, Wenatchapam, Pesquose, Yakama, Shyiks, Know-was-say-ee, and Wish-ham. All 14 groups are now part of the Confederated Tribes and Bands of the Yakama Nation and live on a reservation in central Washington.     On January 29, 1921, seven members of the Yakama nation stopped in Seattle on their way back from Olympia, where they appeared before the Washington State Senate. The 1855 treaty, which guaranteed the right to fish the Yakima River, was threatened by restrictions at the new Prosser Dam in Benton County. This photo shows four members of the delegation, left to right: Chief Lo-páh-hin (Caesar Williams), Yes-to-lah-lemy (Mrs. Kate Williams), Mrs. Homer Watson, and Chief Homer Watson. They wear ceremonial clothing. The beadwork and woven bag are typical of Yakama handicrafts. Chief Lo-páh-hin was a chief from Oregon who joined the delegation; Chief Watson was second in authority among all Yakama groups.     Caption information source: Yakama Nation, retrieved from https://www.yakama.com/about/.

Title: Group of Suquamish people waiting at Colman Dock, Seattle, circa 1911
Notes: The Suquamish tribe lived on Bainbridge Island and fished in the waters of Puget Sound long before Seattle was founded. The Suquamish carved dugout canoes and used them to travel to fishing and hunting grounds across Puget Sound. Fishing, especially for salmon, was of central importance to the Suquamish for both subsistence and culture. Suquamish fishers used subtle environmental clues including tides, numbers of birds and seals, and water levels in streams to establish the best places and times to fish. The 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott reduced Suquamish land to some 7,800 acres at Port Madison, just north of the island on the Kitsap Peninsula. Members of the tribe frequently traveled by steamer from the Port Madison Reservation to Seattle to trade for supplies or transact other business. Today, most Suquamish people live on or around the Port Madison reservation and continue to practice their cultural traditions.     In this photo, a group of Suquamish people waits at Seattle's Colman Dock for the steamer to Bainbridge Island after trying to collect land payments owed by the government. Tribal members have identified the six visible members of the group as, left to right: Doctor Peter, Charlie Youkton, Mrs. Chief Jacob, Chief Jacob Wahelchu, [unknown], and Mary Adams.     Original copy negative.     Caption information source: "History & Culture," Suquamish Tribe, retrieved from https://suquamish.nsn.us/home/about-us/history-culture/

Title: Indigenous family selling baskets in downtown Seattle, circa 1912
Notes: At the turn of 19th to 20th centuries, Indigenous artists in the Pacific Northwest were making baskets and carvings specifically for the tourist trade and were experimenting with form and design. Making baskets for sale became an important income source for many Indigenous families. In this photo, two women and a boy sit by their baskets on Second Avenue, outside the Frederick & Nelson department store. The twined baskets in the image are of the style made by the Makah people of Neah Bay and the Nuu-cha-nulth (formerly called Nootka) people of Vancouver Island.     Caption information source: "Northwest Coast Basketry," by Silvia Koros for the Burke Museum, retrieved from https://www.burkemuseum.org/static/baskets/Teachersguideforbasketry.htm.

Title: Children in front of girls’ dormitory building, Tulalip Indian School, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word “dxwlilap,” meaning “small-mouth bay.”     Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to “civilize” Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     This image shows the youngest students lined up in front of the girls’ dormitory. The upper floor contained the bedrooms (including a sick room), the middle floor had a music room in the left wing, a reading room in the right, and a dining room in the center. Showers and a play room were in the basement.    Caption on image: "Brady photo."    Caption information source: History, Tulalip Tribes, retrieved from https://www.tulaliptribes-nsn.gov/WhoWeAre/History.   Caption information source: Assimilation Through Education: Indian Boarding Schools in the Pacific Northwest, by Carolyn Marr, retrieved from https://content.lib.washington.edu/aipnw/marr.html.

Previous version of Notes (6/2023): The Tulalip Indian School opened on January 23, 1905, and during the next two years it held a capacity enrollment of 200 students.  The boys and girls lived in separate dormitories. Children as young as six years old attended the boarding school.  Older boys and girls were each assigned two of the youngsters to take care of and assist in getting ready for school.  Shown in this photo are the youngest students, lined up in front of the girls’ dormitory.  The upper floor contained the bedrooms (including a sick room), the middle floor had a music room in the left wing, a reading room in the right, and a dining room in the center.  Showers and a play room were in the basement.    Caption on image: "Brady photo."    Photographer Ferd Brady had a studio in Marysville, Washington from 1907 to 1910, then moved to Everett, and finally settled in Anacortes in the 1920s.  In the 1910s, he had a government contract to photograph the people and activities at the Tulalip Indian School, near Marysville.  Brady closed his Everett studio in 1952 and died in 1967. (Everett Public Library, "An Index of Everett Photographers: 1890-1935," p. 13; Anacortes Museum exhibition files.)

Title: Two racing canoes, Tulalip Bay, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    At the Tulalip Indian Reservation, canoe races often took place on the 4th of July. Eleven-person teams competed in many different races with different types of canoes. Women also participated on their own teams, usually with a male bow man and captain. This image shows a race between long canoes. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip reservation and boarding school. Title: Canoe race, Tulalip Bay, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    At the Tulalip Indian Reservation, canoe races often took place on the 4th of July. Here, teams of two boys compete in small dugouts. The canoes shown are the traditional Coast Salish notched-prow style, except for the second from the left, which has the prow of a West Coast style. The former became extremely rare by the middle of the century, as the latter became more numerous. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip reservation and boarding school.     Caption on image: "Little canoe race, Tulalip Indian Boys."     Caption information source: "History," Tulalip Tribes, retrieved from https://www.tulaliptribes-nsn.gov/WhoWeAre/History. Title: Tulalip Indian School building, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     Buildings on the school grounds included the boys’ dormitory, the girls’ dormitory, a machine shop, the hospital, and other structures for the maintenance of the campus. Pupils spent half days in classes in this school building; here they learned spelling, reading, arithmetic, history, geography, and hygiene. The other half of their days were spent doing work to maintain the school and its grounds.     Caption on image: "School building - T.I.S." Title: Tulalip Indian School boys band, 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word “dxwlilap,” meaning “small-mouth bay.”    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     Student bands at the Tulalip school date back to 1860, when the school was operated by Catholic missionaries. That year, the school had 15 students and its all-boys band played in nearby towns to raise money for the school. In 1912, members of the band included, front row, left to right: Fred Curley (Lummi); George Jones (Tulalip); and Alfred Sam (Snohomish) at far right. Top row, left to right are: Joseph Joe; Aloysius Shelton (Tulalip); unknown; Ernest Cladoosby (Swinomish); and Leo George (Tulalip) at far right. The band played in the town of Marysville and traveled to other reservations to perform for special occasions. Title: Boys hoeing garden, Tulalip Indian School, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word “dxwlilap,” meaning “small-mouth bay.”    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Title: Game of Slahal, Treaty Day celebration, Tulalip, 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     Under most circumstances, traditional games such as slahal, the bone game, were discouraged by the "Indian agents" who administered the reservations. On this occasion, the anniversary of the signing of the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, the bone game is a center attraction. Teams have lined up facing each other while a crowd watches. The school boys, in their corduroy uniforms and hats, kneel in the foreground, and some of the girls look down from a balcony of the Girls' Building. Slahal is a gambling game played by many Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest. It involves hiding animal bones in one team's hands while the other guesses which hand holds the bones. Title: Hospital staff, Tulalip Indian School, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     Illness was a constant fear among boarding school students and staff. The influenza epidemic of 1918 hit hard at Tulalip, and there was a very real threat of tuberculosis for many years. The hospital building had two wards, one for boys and one for girls. The dormitories each had a sick room for minor ailments. The staff in this photo include student nurses in training: Josie Cayou (Swinomish); Theresa Young (Tulalip); Myrtle Loughrey (Suquamish); Clara Jones (Swinomish); Emily Limon (Upper Skagit); and Annie Nason (Muckleshoot, in center). Nurse O’Dell and Dr. Buchanan stand at the rear.     Caption information source: "History," Tulalip Tribes, retrieved from https://www.tulaliptribes-nsn.gov/WhoWeAre/History.   Caption information source: "Assimilation Through Education: Indian Boarding Schools in the Pacific Northwest," by Carolyn Marr, retrieved from https://content.lib.washington.edu/aipnw/marr.html.

Title: Baseball team, Tulalip Indian School, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     Baseball, which somewhat resembles the Indigenous game of stick ball, was the most popular sport among students. In earlier years, players fashioned their own handmade bats and sometimes played barehanded. On the team pictured here are Clemont Bob, second from left in back row; Robert Shelton, third from right; Roy Loughrey, second from right; Joseph Joe, far right; and Augustus Day, seated on right. In the back row, holding a pennant, is William Shelton, an employee of the school and Robert’s father. William Shelton (1868-1938), named Wha-ceh-dub or Whah-kay-dub in his native language of Lushootseed, was a cultural leader of the Snohomish and expert woodworker and carver of story poles. Title: Tulalip men working on a log boom, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."     Loggers cleared most of the reservation land in the first part of the 20th century. The cut logs were hauled to the bay and floated in log booms to sawmills located throughout the area. The Tulalip Indian School also encouraged its students to become farmers, which required the clearing of forests on the reservation. Indigenous men, like the three seen here, found employment in all aspects of the lumber industry.     The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip reservation and boarding school. Title: Wood chopping crew, Tulalip Indian School, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     Every student at the boarding school spent at least half of his or her day working in some part of the operation. Boys rotated about every six weeks between jobs as carpenters, engineers, farmers or dairymen; girls were assigned to sewing, darning, laundry and kitchen work. As part of their regular work assignment, some of the young men chopped, split, and stacked hundreds of cords of wood to feed the steam boilers which supplied heat and power to the school buildings. Shown in this photo are Sebastian Williams (second from left), Woody Loughrey (fifth from left) and Clarence Shelton (third from right).     Caption on image: "Engineer boys T.I.S." Lucy and Bill Dunbar are shown with their children Josephine and Billy, Jr., who both attended the school. Title: Young women working in kitchen, Tulalip Indian School, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     Every student at the boarding school spent at least half of his or her day working in some part of the operation. Boys rotated about every six weeks between jobs as carpenters, engineers, farmers or dairymen; girls were assigned to sewing, darning, laundry and kitchen work. The students raised most of the school’s food on the grounds and prepared it in the kitchen. In this photo, Mrs. Ryman, the cook, supervises bread baking. Identified students are: Laura Wilbur (Swinomish), child kneeling at left; Julia Abbott (Lummi), second from left; Catherine Edwards (Swinomish); and Isabella Louke (Muckleshoot). Title: Tulalip Indian School grounds, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     The Tulalip Indian School was situated on reservation land along the shores of Tulalip Bay. During the early years of the school nearly all transportation was by water. A steamer arrived at the dock on a regular schedule carrying mail and visitors. After a fire in 1902 destroyed the older St. Anne’s Catholic Mission School, which had been at this site since 1861, the federal government funded construction of the buildings shown in this photograph. The new school opened in 1905. The Tulalip Indian School closed in 1932. Title: Sawmill, Tulalip Indian School, circa 1912
Notes: The Tulalip Tribes are a confederation of several Coast Salish peoples including the Snohomish, Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit, Suiattle, Samish, Stillaguamish, and other allied tribes and bands. In the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott, these groups ceded most of their land to the United States and reserved the Tulalip Indian Reservation for their permanent homeland. They also reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The name Tulalip comes from the Coast Salish word "dxwlilap," meaning "small-mouth bay."    Catholic missionaries opened a boarding school on the Tulalip reservation in 1857. After a few years, the school began receiving funding from the federal government and in 1902 the government fully took over the school. That year, the original school buildings burned down, and a new school reopened in 1905. The school had a capacity of 200 students, who were as young as six. The photographer Ferdinand Brady had a government contract in the 1910s to photograph the people and activities around the Tulalip Indian School. The Tulalip school was one of many boarding schools for Indigenous children across the US. These schools were an attempt to "civilize" Indigenous peoples by forcing their children to assimilate to white-dominated Western society. One of the primary ways the schools undertook this goal was forcing students to speak English exclusively. Severe punishment, including physical punishment, was imposed when students spoke their native languages or otherwise resisted school authorities.     A sawmill located next to Tulalip Creek served the entire community. When wood or lumber were needed, logs were hauled in log booms across the bay to the mill. The creek was later dammed to supply electricity, and a powerhouse was built at the mill site. William Shelton (Snohomish), an employee of the school, served as the sawyer at this time. Shelton (1868-1938), named Wha-ceh-dub or Whah-kay-dub in his native language of Lushootseed, was a cultural leader of the Snohomish and expert woodworker and carver of story poles. A member of the Tulalip Tribes contacted by the Museum of History and Industry identified the group in this photo as the milking brigade. Title: Young Doctor and his wife Lizzie, Neah Bay, circa 1900
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     Young Doctor (circa 1851-1934) was a well-known Makah carver and musician whose life spanned a period of intense cultural change. Shown in this photograph with his wife Lizzie, Young Doctor holds an adze and a partially carved staff. Carvings of model canoes, a human figure, and a whale with floats attached are arranged on the steps of the building.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. In his memoir "Indian Days at Neah Bay", McCurdy stated that none could match the precise skill of Young Doctor, who had learned his craft from his father and was aided by spirit helpers. Title: Atlieu, Nuu-cha-nulth carver, Neah Bay, circa 1900
Notes: The Nuu-chah-nulth are a group of 14 First Nations peoples living on the west side of Vancouver Island: Ditidaht, Huu-ay-aht, Hupacasath, Tse-shaht, Uchucklesaht, Ahousaht, Hesquiaht, Tla-o-qui-aht, Toquaht, Ucluelet, Ehattesaht, Kyuqout/Checlesaht, Mowachat/Muchalaht, and Nuchatlaht. They share cultural traditions and language but remain distinct nations, each with a hereditary chief. The Nuu-chah-nulth peoples were previously called the Nootka after European colonizers misunderstood their name and assumed them all to be one tribe, but they collectively chose this new name for themselves in 1978. Fishing and whaling were important parts of Nuu-chah-nulth culture, and they continue to protect their hunting and fishing rights on traditional territory. The Nuu-chah-nulth also have a tradition of skilled woodworking; they build totem poles, multifamily homes, and large oceangoing canoes. Over the 19th century, the increasing presence of settlers displaced the Nuu-chah-nulth from their historic land and they were forced onto reserves created by the Canadian government. As of 2022, the Nuu-chah-nulth Tribal Council represents about 10,000 enrolled members across 14 First Nations on Vancouver Island.     The renowned carver Atlieu (Charlie Williams) came from a Tla-o-qui-aht village on Vancouver Island but lived part of the time with the Makah in Neah Bay, Washington. He received several medals from the Canadian government in recognition of his woodcarving and metalwork, one of which he wears in this photograph. The ceremonial mask he is painting is a good example of Nuu-chah-nulth-style carving. The yew-wood club at the far left shows Atlieu’s distinctive style, with its intertwining animal figures.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     This photograph is a rare view of the inside of a traditional Makah longhouse around 1900. The smoke holes in the roof are open to let in light, fish are drying on racks near the ceiling, and rolled-up sails are suspended from ropes. Sealskins full of oil, various pots, baskets, a washboard, and cattail mats can also be seen. Traditional Makah longhouses were constructed of split cedar planks placed horizontally and lashed to upright poles with lengths of twisted cedar rope. Sleeping platforms lined the walls and each family had its own cooking place on the earthen floor.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. Title: Makah woman making baskets at Neah Bay, circa 1905
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     Makah women have a tradition of basketry back to time immemorial. They use grasses, tree bark, or roots to make a variety of baskets and mats for various uses. Some Makah baskets are so tightly woven that they are watertight. Today, the tradition is carried on by both women and men. This photo, taken sometime between about 1900 and 1910, shows a Makah basketmaker on the beach, probably at Port Townsend. She is using cedar bark strips to make a dry storage container.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. Title: Group seated on the beach with trade items, Port Townsend, circa 1900
Notes: The people in this photograph are not identified, but the items they brought with them in their large sea-going canoes are visible-- bundles of dried cattails for weaving mats and a large, decorated Chinese trunk. The woman in the center appears to be holding a mirror.     The buildings in the distant background indicate the location is probably Port Townsend, Washington. At this time, many Indigenous people traveled to Port Townsend to conduct trade on the beach. Most of the subjects of this image have their backs to the camera. At least one surviving account from Port Townsend indicates that white photographers often photographed Indigenous people, and that some of the Indigenous subjects resented being photographed, asked for compensation, or attempted to avoid being photographed.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894.    Caption information source: Charles T. Hommel, A Guide to Historical Photograph Collections in Seattle, p. 33  Caption information source: "The Indian and His Point of View," by Katherine McCurdy, The Westerner, Vol. IV, No. 5, April 1906.

Title: Makah woman drying fish on a rack, Neah Bay, circa 1900
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     Halibut and salmon, the staples of the diet of Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest, were either dried or smoked for winter use. In this photograph taken at Neah Bay, a Makah woman dries thinly-sliced fish in the sun. The scarecrows on the ends of the racks were intended to frighten away hungry birds.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. Title: Two Makah basketmakers, Neah Bay, circa 1900
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     These Makah women of Neah Bay demonstrate the distinctive lidded baskets, sometimes called "trinket baskets," for which the Makah are well-known. The bundled grass, which can be woven over a foundation of cedar bark, can be dyed various colors or left its natural cream color. These baskets combine geometric with naturalistic designs, and some are so tightly woven they are watertight. The Makah traded among Native groups as well as to non-Native collectors.    The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. Title: Coast Salish canoe in Port Townsend Bay, circa 1900
Notes: The Coast Salish style canoe was designed for use in the calm waters of Puget Sound and its many small bays and inlets. Both the prow and the stern curve upwards from a rounded bottom. Salish canoes were often painted black with brightly colored figures near the prow and stern. The Coast Salish style of canoe was more lightly constructed than other canoes built by Indigenous peoples and was not suited for longer voyages or in rough waters. It was also not as useful for fishing, carrying cargo, or raiding and as a result the style was gradually replaced by the more robust West Coast style of canoe, originally built by the Nuu-Chah-Nulth of Vancouver Island.     This image shows a Coast Salish style canoe piloted by an Indigenous person in Port Townsend Bay on the Olympic Peninsula. A few other watercraft are visible in the right background, including a sailing ship and a steamship. The Klallam (also spelled S'Klallam), a Coast Salish group, lived in and around Port Townsend and the subject of this image may be a Klallam.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. Title: West Coast style canoe with two sails, circa 1900
Notes: By the turn of the 20th century, Indigenous seafarers adapted cloth sails, usually of the sprit-rig type seen in this image. Traditional sails of woven mats and wood slats had been used prior to the arrival of Europeans, but they were replaced by cloth once the Native peoples began trading with the settlers.     This photograph was probably taken in Port Townsend Bay or along the Strait of Juan de Fuca. It shows a West Coast style canoe equipped with a European style sail. The West Coast style of canoe was originally developed by the Nuu-Chah-Nulth peoples of Vancouver Island. It had a flatter bottom than other canoe styles and a vertical stern, making it more stable in rougher waters and able to carry more cargo. As a result, West Coast style canoes became the most common style in the Pacific Northwest during the late 19th century.     The photographer, James McCurdy, was born in Port Townsend in 1872. He spent many years of his childhood in Neah Bay on the Makah reservation and returned to Port Townsend in 1894. Title: Indigenous women picking hops, Snoqualmie Hop Ranch, circa 1895
Notes: From the late 1860s to the early 1890s, hop farming was an important activity in the valleys of the Puget Sound region, including Puyallup, White River, and Snoqualmie. Indigenous workers came from throughout the Pacific Northwest, Canada, and Alaska (but especially from regional tribes like the Puyallup, Snoqualmie, Muckleshoot, Duwamish, Sammamish, Lummi, and Nisqually) as a seasonal labor force to harvest these crops in late summer and early autumn. This seasonal work gave them a chance to earn the money they needed to buy things in a cash economy.     In this 1890s photo, taken at Snoqualmie Hop Ranch in western Washington state, two Indigenous women stand in a hop field holding traditional cedar bark baskets. Other baskets filled with the pale hop blossoms sit on the ground in the background (right). Title: Pat Kanim, Snoqualmie Chief, circa 1855
Notes: The Snoqualmie people are a Coast Salish group who have lived in the Snoqualmie River Valley since time immemorial. They made dugout canoes which they used to navigate the river and reach Puget Sound. Traditionally the Snoqualmie burned off the bottom lands of the Snoqualmie Valley to create open areas that ensured an abundance of edible plants for foraging as well as supplied space for game animals to feed. In the early 19th century, the Snoqualmie were among the most powerful tribes around Puget Sound. They exerted economic influence over neighboring groups from Whidbey Island to Snoqualmie Pass. The Snoqualmie signed the Treaty of Point Elliott in 1855, ceding their land to the United States. They were temporarily assigned to live on the Tulalip reservation and were promised a reservation of their own. However, the US government reneged on its promise and no land was allocated for the Snoqualmie, most of whom moved back to their historic lands or stayed on the Tulalip reservation. The Snoqualmie finally received a reservation on their historic land in 1999.    This image is a portrait of Patkanim (or Pat Kanim), the chief of the Snoqualmie and Snohomish in the mid 19th century. In the 1840s, he wanted to force out the early white settlers. However, after visiting San Francisco in 1850, Patkanim decided that any fight against the settlers would be hopeless. He signed the Treaty of Point Elliott in 1855 and aided the settlers against other Indigenous groups in the war of 1855-1856. Patkanim died in 1858 on the Tulalip Reservation.     Photographer George N. Moore copied this portrait in the 1880s from an earlier photograph of Patkanim. Title: Industrial Boarding School buildings on the Puyallup Reservation, circa 1885
Notes: The Puyallup people are a Coast Salish group whose historic lands are along the Puyallup River Valley. They call themselves "Spuyalepabs" in their native language of Lushootseed, meaning "people from the bend at the bottom of the river." Before settlers arrived, the Puyallup lived in villages that spread from the Cascade foothills to the shores of Puget Sound. In 1854, Puyallup leaders signed the Medicine Creek Treaty under duress. The Puyallup ceded most of their land to the US in this treaty, but due to US government treaty violations in the size and location of reservations, the Puyallup peoples joined what is now called the Puget Sound War in 1855-1856. After the war ended, the treaty was renegotiated and the Puyallup reservation was enlarged. Since then, the Puyallup have fought for tribal rights, including in the fish wars of the 1960s and 70s and the Puyallup Land Claims Settlement in 1990.    Starting in the middle of the 19th century, church groups and the United States government set up boarding schools for Indigenous children. Here, children from many tribes were taught to speak English and were educated with a focus on agriculture and manual skills. They were separated from their elders, discouraged from learning their tribal traditions, and punished for speaking languages other than English. This photo shows the buildings and students of the Puyallup Indian School on the Puyallup Reservation, sometime between 1880 and 1889. The Puyallup Indian School opened in 1860 but expanded in the 1880s and 1890s, when a number of new buildings were added, and the school grew from 125 to more than 350 pupils. Later called the Industrial Boarding School and the Cushman School, it remained open until 1920. By that time, most Indigenous children attended local public schools. Title: Pilchuck Julia, Snohomish, 1915
Notes: The Snohomish (written Sduhubš in their language) are a Coast Salish people who have lived along the Snohomish River since time immemorial. Their largest village was Hibulb, near the mouth of the river in what is now Everett. Like their other Coast Salish neighbors, the Snohomish used dugout canoes to travel along rivers and around Puget Sound. Salmon fishing was important to the Snohomish, both for sustenance and for cultural reasons. In 1855, Snohomish leaders signed the Treaty of Point Elliott. They ceded land to the United States but reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. The Snohomish were temporarily assigned to live on the Tulalip reservation and were promised their own reservation. However, the US government later reneged on this promise and most Snohomish people remained on the Tulalip reservation. As of 2023, the Snohomish are not a federally-recognized tribe.     Pilchuck Julia, of the Snohomish people, was born around 1840 and witnessed the signing of the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott. After the treaty, she and her husband Pilchuck Jack stayed at their home on the Pilchuck River, near the town of Snohomish, Washington. Pilchuck Julia supported the family by making baskets and by selling clams, salmon, and berries. She was also known for her accurate weather predictions. During her lifetime, Julia was a much-photographed figure. Pilchuck Julia died of smallpox in 1923 and is buried in the G.A.R. Cemetery in Snohomish. The Pilchuck Julia Boat Landing in Snohomish was named in her honor in 2017.     Caption on image: "Pilchuck Julia, [copyright] 1915 by Wm. Douglas." Title: Quileute children and teachers, La Push, circa 1887
Notes: The Quileute are an Indigenous people whose historic lands are on the west side of the Olympic Peninsula, in the valleys of the Quillayute and Hoh Rivers. The Quileute are not related to either the Makah to the north or the Coast Salish peoples of western Washington, and the Quileute language is unrelated to any other in the world. Quileute land is directly exposed to the Pacific Ocean and receives about 9.5 feet of average yearly rainfall. To protect themselves, the Quileute made rainproof hats and clothing using the inner layer of cedar bark. The Quileute signed the Treaty of Olympia in 1856, in which they ceded their land and agreed to move to a reservation. In the treaty, the Quileute reserved rights for hunting, fishing, and gathering at all usual and accustomed places. However, because their land was so remote, reservations were not established until 1889 and 1893. Today, most Quileutes live on either the Quileute or the Hoh reservations.    In 1882, A.W. Smith established a school on Quileute land. He renamed Quileute individuals after Biblical characters and figures from US history. Seven years later Smith would become the "Indian agent" when the Quileute reservation was established. In this photo, Smith (left center) and his wife (right) pose with a group of Quileute school children next to a recently-built structure which may be the school.     Caption information source: "History", Quileute Nation, retrieved from https://quileutenation.org/history/#.

Title: Quileute Indians in a western Washington hop field, 1904
Notes: The Quileute are an Indigenous people whose historic lands are on the west side of the Olympic Peninsula, in the valleys of the Quillayute and Hoh Rivers. The Quileute are not related to either the Makah to the north or the Coast Salish peoples of western Washington and the Quileute language is unrelated to any other in the world. Quileute land is directly exposed to the Pacific Ocean and receives about 9.5 feet of average yearly rainfall. To protect themselves, the Quileute made rainproof hats and clothing using the inner layer of cedar bark. The Quileute signed the Treaty of Olympia in 1856, in which they ceded their land and agreed to move to a reservation. In the treaty, the Quileute reserved rights for hunting, fishing, and gathering at all usual and accustomed places. However, because their land was so remote, reservations were not established until 1889 and 1893. Today, most Quileutes live on either the Quileute or the Hoh reservations.    From the late 1860s to the early 1890s, hop farming was an important activity in the valleys of the Puget Sound region, including Puyallup, White River, and Snoqualmie. Indigenous workers came from throughout the Pacific Northwest, Canada, and Alaska as a seasonal labor force to harvest crops in late summer and early autumn. Some Quileute people traveled all the way from the west coast of Washington's Olympic Peninsula to Puget Sound to pick hops. They relied on wages from seasonal labor to purchase goods in the currency-based economy of settlers. In 1889, a settler burned down the Quileute village of La Push while the inhabitants were away picking hops. The fire destroyed many of the last remaining masks, baskets, hunting equipment, and sacred items from before contact with the settlers.     This image shows a group of Quileute people posing for a photo in a hop field. Woven baskets to carry the hops can be seen in the foreground. This image is a stereograph – two nearly identical images printed together to produce a 3D effect when seen through a special viewer. Davis, New York City, and St. Louis, Mo.    Caption information source: "History", Quileute Nation, retrieved from https://quileutenation.org/history/#.

Title: Game of slahal on a Puget Sound beach, circa 1884
Notes: Slahal, also called the bone game, is one of many games played by Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest. A team member held up their hands, each of which contained a small bone, and the members of the opposite team tried to guess if a marked bone was in the right or left hand. Slahal often also involved gambling between the teams. Stakes could be high, and the games might last for hours.     In this photo, taken sometime before Washington became a state in 1889, a group of Indigenous people play the bone game near their beached canoes. The two teams sit opposite one another in the sand. Some team members hold sticks which are used for scoring and for keeping up a rhythmic beat.    Caption on image: "Indians gambling, Puget Sound, W.T." ; "Washington Territory and Oregon Views."   Part of series entitled: "Washington Territory and Oregon Views"

Title: Steilacoom John and Annie, circa 1905
Notes: The Steilacoom are a Coast Salish people whose historic lands are near the current town of Steilacoom, southwest of Tacoma. The Steilacoom consisted of five bands: Steilacoom, Sastuck, Spanaway, Tilhlow, and Segwallitchew. Unlike many of their neighbors the Steilacoom did not live near a glacier-fed river, but on land featuring a group of lakes and creeks. The Steilacoom were affected by settlers earlier than most other Indigenous peoples in Washington. Settlers encroached on their land starting in the 1830s, and the first incorporated town north of the Columbia River was in Steilacoom territory. In 1854, Steilacoom leaders signed the Medicine Creek Treaty and ceded their land to the United States. The US government expected Steilacoom land to be heavily populated with settlers and so did not assign the Steilacoom a reservation. Instead, the Steilacoom were assigned to live on neighboring reservations. Many refused to leave, however, and have remained on their historic lands. The Steilacoom Tribe is not federally recognized.     Steilacoom John was a leader of the Steilacoom Tribe and a son of Ce-col-quin, a signer of the 1854 Medicine Creek Treaty. In this photograph, John and his wife Goe-lit-sah (also called Anna or Annie) are seated in front of their home with a basket and other household items. This image is a stereograph – two nearly identical images printed together to produce a 3D effect when seen through a special viewer. A caption on the image describes John and Annie as "Siwash Indians." The term "Siwash" was once used as a general term for Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest, but it is now considered derogatory.    Caption on image: "Steilacoom John and Annie. Title: Indigenous canoes docked at the Seattle waterfront, circa 1892
Notes: In 1865 the Board of Trustees of Seattle passed Ordinance No. 5 banning Indigenous people from living in the city unless they worked for a non-Indigenous resident and lived on their employer’s property. Despite this attempt to enforce separation between Indigenous people and the settlers, Seattle depended on Indigenous people. Settlers relied on Native people for domestic work and for trade of fish, shellfish, and baskets. Indigenous people from across the Pacific Northwest also harvested hops in agricultural areas to the south and east of Seattle.     Because they were excluded from the rest of the city, many Indigenous people stayed on Ballast Island, either when passing through, temporarily stopping, or living on the island year-round. Ballast Island was in the harbor at the foot of Washington Street and was created when sailing ships dumped their ballast in Elliott Bay in order to take on cargo. The only place close to Seattle’s business district where Indigenous people were allowed to live, Ballast Island lacked a source of fresh water or permanent structures. As the waterfront grew in the 1890s, Ballast Island was gradually covered and by the time the seawall was built in 1916, the island was almost completely gone and its Indigenous residents had again been displaced.    This image shows several canoes moored at Ballast Island, with an encampment visible on the island and the growing cityscape in the background. Indigenous people from across the Pacific Northwest also harvested hops in agricultural areas to the south and east of Seattle.     Because they were excluded from the rest of the city, many Indigenous people stayed on Ballast Island, either when passing through, temporarily stopping, or living on the island year-round. Ballast Island was in the harbor at the foot of Washington Street and was created when sailing ships dumped their ballast in Elliott Bay in order to take on cargo. The only place close to Seattle’s business district where Indigenous people were allowed to live, Ballast Island lacked a source of fresh water or permanent structures. As the waterfront grew in the 1890s, Ballast Island was gradually covered and by the time the seawall was built in 1916, the island was almost completely gone and its Indigenous residents had again been displaced.    This image shows canoes beached on Ballast Island, a few of them converted into tents. Dugout shelters are also visible behind the canoes.     Caption information source: "Exile to Ballast Island," Duwamish Tribe, retrieved from https://www.duwamishtribe.org/exile-to-ballast-island  Caption information source: "Seattle Board of Trustees passes ordinance, calling for removal of Indians from the town, on February 7, 1865," by Jennifer Ott, HistoryLink essay #10979, retrieved from https://www.historylink.org/file/10979

Title: Jim Yellakanim, Nooksack chief, circa 1898
Notes: The Nooksack are a Coast Salish people whose historic lands centered on the Nooksack River drainage basin, from the shore to around Mount Baker in the east. They have their own language, also named Nooksack. On the edges of Nooksack land and in offshore waters, resources were shared with neighboring peoples, to whom the Nooksack were linked by shared descent or marriage ties. The Nooksack were party to the Treaty of Point Elliott in 1855 and ceded their land in exchange for fishing, hunting, and gathering rights but the Nooksack did not receive a reservation. Many Nooksack refused to leave their homes and in the 1870s, they claimed homesteads on their historic land. The Nooksack tribe received a small reservation in 1970 and was federally recognized in 1973. Today, many of the 2,000 Nooksack tribal members live near their historic lands and continue to fish, both for income and to maintain cultural practices.     "Jim" Yellakanim Seclamatan was a leader of the Nooksack people. He claimed a homestead in the upper Nooksack Valley, just outside the town of Lynden, Washington. Yellakanim died in April 1911 at the age of nearly 100 at the home of his granddaughter, Emily Williams.
