Title: Cheholtz family in front of fishing shack, near Castle Rock, Washington, circa 1885
Notes: The Cowlitz People are a Coast Salish group whose historic lands are along the Cowlitz and Lewis Rivers, in what is now southwestern Washington. Traditionally, the annual cycle of resource gathering determined where the Cowlitz People traveled and at what time of year – from river fishing in the spring, gathering roots and berries in summer and fall, and making crafts and repairing nets in the winter to prepare for the next spring. In 1855, Cowlitz leaders left negotiations with the Washington territorial government when the government required them to abandon their homeland in exchange for a reservation on the coast, to be shared with the other Indigenous peoples of southwestern Washington. The Cowlitz signed no treaty with the United States, but after the Puget Sound War of 1855-56, the Cowlitz’s land was taken by the US and sold to settlers. Many Cowlitz people remained in their historic lands and maintained their tribal ties to each other through the 20th century. The Cowlitz Indian Tribe was federally recognized in 2000 and the Cowlitz reservation was established near Ridgefield, Washington in 2010.     This image shows the Cheholtz family, from the Toutle River band of the Cowlitz people. From left to right: Kathleen Cheholtz, Elisha Cheholtz, John Cheholtz, Peter Cheholtz (seated), Lemmea Cheholtz, and Henry Cheholtz. The man wearing a hat standing behind Peter is unidentified. Henry was the chief of the Toutle River band and Kathleen and Lemmea were his wives. The Cheholtz family lived on the banks of the Cowlitz River near the town of Castle Rock and this photo was taken in front of a fishing shack as they returned home.    Caption information source: Email exchange with Clarence Koch, descendant of the Cheholtz family, November 2022   Caption information source: "Cultural Resources Department," Cowlitz Indian Tribe, retrieved from https://www.cowlitz.org/services/cultural-resources.html   Caption information source: "That the People May Live: The Cowlitz Tribe’s Journey of Peace and Justice," by Eugene A. Wiggins, Journal of Pacific Rim Psychology, 1(2), page 44-53, retrieved from https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1375/prp.1.2.44   Caption information source: "Castle Rock," by Vicki Selander, Arcadia Publishing, page 10

Title: Quileutes landing provisions at La Push, circa 1900
Notes: The Quileute are an Indigenous people whose historic lands are on the west side of the Olympic Peninsula, in the valleys of the Quillayute and Hoh Rivers. The Quileute are not related to either the Makah to the north or the Coast Salish peoples of western Washington, and the Quileute language is unrelated to any other in the world. Quileute land is directly exposed to the Pacific Ocean and receives about 9.5 feet of average yearly rainfall. To protect themselves, the Quileute made rainproof hats and clothing using the inner layer of cedar bark. The Quileute signed the Treaty of Olympia in 1856, in which they ceded their land and agreed to move to a reservation. In the treaty, the Quileute reserved rights for hunting, fishing, and gathering at all usual and accustomed places. However, because their land was so remote, reservations were not established until 1889 and 1893. Today, most Quileutes live on either the Quileute or the Hoh reservations.    Because Quileute land was distant from road or rail connections, the Quileute obtained supplies by loading up their large sea-going canoes. In this photo, a group unloads large sacks at First Beach, which borders the village of La Push. The canoes are of the West Coast style with an upturned prow and a vertical stern. The caption written on the image misidentifies the location as Mora, which is slightly up the Quillayute River from La Push.     Caption on image: "Indians landing provisions at Mora, Washington"     Caption information source: "History", Quileute Nation, retrieved from https://quileutenation.org/history/#.   Caption information from Jay Powell and Vickie Jensen, Quileute: An Introduction to the Indians of La Push, n.p. Nearby Mora is not directly on the beach.

Title: Indigenous men, women and children working in hop field, Kent, circa 1895
Notes: From the late 1860s to the early 1890s, hop farming was an important activity in the valleys of the Puget Sound region, including Puyallup, White River, and Snoqualmie. Indigenous workers came from throughout the Pacific Northwest, Canada, and Alaska (but especially from regional tribes like the Puyallup, Snoqualmie, Muckleshoot, Duwamish, Sammamish, Lummi, and Nisqually) as a seasonal labor force to harvest these crops in late summer and early autumn. This seasonal work gave them a chance to earn the money they needed to buy things in a cash economy.     Many Native families traveled to the hop fields where they camped out during the harvest. Some returned to the same hop fields each year, and this became an important social event. Schools were closed during the harvest so that children could help in the fields. This photo, probably from the 1890s, shows Indigenous men, women, and children at work in a hop field near Kent, Washington. The dried blossoms of the hop plant, called cones, fill the large baskets in the foreground.     Caption on image: "Indian hop pickers at Kent."     Caption information source: "Indigenous Hop Pickers in Western Washington" by Hans Zeiger, HistoryLink.org Essay 21295

Title: Chief Chits-A-Man-Han and his wife, circa 1884
Notes: The S’Klallam (also spelled Klallam) are a Coast Salish people whose historic lands stretch across the northern Olympic Peninsula from the current location of Port Townsend to the Hoko River, near Makah lands. They also lived on Whidbey Island and on the south shore of Vancouver Island. The S’Klallam lived in permanent longhouses during the winter, but in other seasons individual families spread out and camped at traditional sites to fish, hunt, or gather resources. In 1855, the S’Klallam signed the Point No Point Treaty and ceded their land to the United States but reserved rights to hunt, fish, and gather at usual and accustomed sites. The treaty stated that the S’Klallam would move to a reservation at Skokomish, but this site was distant from their traditional lands and most S’Klallams refused to leave. Beginning in the 1870s, many S’Klallam individuals privately purchased land on their traditional territory. As a result, separate S’Klallam groups emerged, which last to this day. One of the tribes lives on Vancouver Island at Becher Bay. The other three are on the northern Olympic Peninsula – the Lower Elwha Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1939), the Port Gamble S’Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1936), and the Jamestown S’Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1981).    This is a portrait of Chits-A-Man-Han (nicknamed the “Duke of York” by the settlers) and his wife. He was chief of the S’Klallam in the 1850s and was one of the signers of the Point No Point Treaty. This image is a composite, created by combining separate photos of Chits-A-Man-Han and his wife. Title: Chesheeahud and others in a canoe on Lake Union, Seattle, circa 1885
Notes: Chesheeahud (also spelled Cheshiahud) was a Duwamish chief and guide to the lakes and rivers around what is now Seattle, living between the mid-19th and early 20th centuries. He led a village called hehs-KWEE-kweel (meaning Skate), at the south edge of the mouth of Union Bay onto Lake Washington. hehs-KWEE-kweel was near a vital portage used by the Duwamish between Lake Union and Lake Washington. Chesheeahud and his wife Tleebuleetsa lived on a plot of land located at Edgewater Park near the point at the south edge of the mouth of Union Bay onto Lake Washington. They were the last Duwamish people to live on Lake Union as the city grew and dislocated the Indigenous residents. Because of this, the settlers often called them the "last of the Lake Union Indians." Chesheeahud was also called "Lake Union John" and the derogatory name "Chudups (also spelled Chodups) John" by the settlers, while Tleebuleetsa was called "Madeline." After Tleebuleetsa died, Chesheeahud moved to the Port Madison reservation, where many other Duwamish people had been displaced to after the Treaty of Point Elliott in 1855.    In this photo, Chesheeahud and several other people sit in a canoe on Lake Union. A mast sticks out beyond the vessel's notched prow. These canoes carried enough supplies to last for journeys lasting several months and could travel far inland on the many rivers in the region. This Coast Salish canoe design was later replaced by the West Coast style through contact with tribes from the Olympic Peninsula and Vancouver Island.     Caption information source: "Chesheeahud," Duwamish Tribe, retrieved from https://www.duwamishtribe.org/cheshiahud

Title: Indigenous woman and canoe at the Seattle waterfront, 1898
Notes: Indigenous people from many parts of the Pacific Northwest came to Seattle to trade and buy supplies. In this photo, a woman holding a basket stands by a large canoe at the Seattle waterfront. The design of the canoe and her hat suggest that she is from one of the First Nations in Vancouver Island or another part of coastal Canada. Her canoe is of the Northern style, designed for long journeys in open water. It has a high prow, flared sides, and a rounded bottom to help with speed and buoyancy. The photo was taken in Seattle, two blocks south of King Street, near First Avenue. Title: Captain Billy and woman on horseback, circa 1900
Notes: The Yakama (formerly spelled Yakima) people have lived in the Columbia River basin since time immemorial. During the winter, they lived in permanent villages built on the valley floor, where the climate was most temperate. Starting in spring, they traveled along the rivers and into the hills to gather food. Some gathered roots and berries, and others fished in rivers, especially the Columbia and the Yakima. In 1855, a confederation of 14 tribal groups signed the Yakama Nation Treaty with the United States and ceded most of their traditional lands, but reserved rights for hunting, gathering, and fishing at all usual and accustomed places. These groups were: Kah-miltpah, Palouse, Klickitat, See-ap-Cat, Klinquit, Sk-in-pah, Li-ay-was, Oche-Chotes, Wenatchapam, Pesquose, Yakama, Shyiks, Know-was-say-ee, and Wish-ham. All 14 groups are now part of the Confederated Tribes and Bands of the Yakama Nation and live on a reservation in central Washington.     This image taken by a Yakima-area photographer, shows a Yakama man identified as Captain Billy and a woman whose name is unknown, possibly his wife. Captain Billy wears animal skin decorations in his hair, and the woman carries a cornhusk bag on her horse's saddle. Both horses wear feathers on their bridles. Writing on the image describes the woman as a ""squaw."" This word is a sexist and racist slur used to refer to Indigenous North American women.     Caption on image: ""Captain Billy and squaw""     Caption information source: Yakama Nation, retrieved from https://www.yakama.com/about/

Title: Plateau man with a dentalium necklace, circa 1900
Notes: The Indigenous peoples of the Columbia Plateau include many different tribal groups. The Plateau peoples’ historic lands are in what is now British Columbia, Washington, Idaho, Montana, and Oregon. In Washington, the Yakama, Nez Perce, Spokane, Colville, and other Plateau tribes live east of the Cascade Range in the Columbia River watershed.     In this portrait, part of a series taken in a Yakima-area photographer's studio, a young Indigenous man poses wearing a beaded belt, necklace, choker, armbands, and earrings. The large horn-shaped dentalium shells in his necklace came from the waters off Vancouver Island and were traded long distances to inland tribes. Traditionally, both men and women wore shell and bead ornaments. The dentalium shells were often interspersed with blue or red glass beads. Title: Mattie Spencer, Klikitat woman, circa 1900
Notes: The Klickitat (also spelled Klikitat) are an Indigenous group whose historic lands are along the Klickitat and White Salmon Rivers east of the Cascade mountains in Washington. Their language is related to the language of the Yakama, their eastern neighbors. The Klickitat fished for salmon in the rivers of their homeland and were also involved in trade among different Indigenous groups because of their convenient location near the Columbia River between Coast Salish tribes to the west and other tribes further east. In 1855, the Klickitat signed a treaty ceding their land to the United States while reserving rights to fish, hunt, and gather at all usual and accustomed places. The Klickitat were assigned to live on the Yakama reservation and today most Klickitats are part of the Confederated Tribes and Bands of the Yakama Nation.     This portrait of a young woman, identified by the subject's granddaughter as Mattie Spencer, is part of a series taken in a Yakima-area photography studio early in the 20th century. She holds a cornhusk bag with a typical geometric design and wears a patterned blanket, beaded belt, necklace and earrings.    Caption information source: "Western Oregon Klickitats," by Robert Boyd, R. Scott Byram, David Lewis, Oregon Encyclopedia, retrieved from https://www.oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/western_oregon_klickitats/#.Y2F9Z3bMKUk

Title: Unveiling the totem pole at Pioneer Square, Seattle, 1899
Notes: This Tlingit totem was carved around 1790 to honor a tribal woman named Chief-of-All-Women and it was placed in the village of Tongass on the Alaska coast. In 1899, a group of leading Seattle businessmen on a goodwill tour of southeastern Alaska stole the totem and brought it back to Pioneer Square. The businessmen were indicted for the theft, but the case was later dismissed. The Seattle Post-Intelligencer, which sponsored the tour, eventually paid a $500 fine to the Tlingit Tribe. After rot and fire damaged the original pole in 1938, Tlingit craftsmen including several descendants of the carvers of the original pole, carved a replica and donated it to Seattle to replace the original.     In this photo, taken in October 1899, a large crowd has gathered for the dedication of the original totem pole.     Caption information source: "Seattle’s Totem Poles," by Viola Garfield, Thistle Press, 1996.   Caption information source: "Stolen totem pole unveiled in Seattle's Pioneer Square on October 18, 1899," by David Wilma, HistoryLink, retrieved from https://www.historylink.org/File/2076

Previous version of Notes (6/2023): The totem pole in Pioneer Square has been a Seattle landmark since 1899.  That year, a group of Seattle businessmen visited Tongass, a Tlingit village in southeastern Alaska. They thought the village was deserted and removed a 50-foot tall totem pole as a souvenir.  The men brought the pole back to Seattle and had it set up in Pioneer Square. They were later fined for the theft.  The pole was originally created as a memorial to a woman of the Raven Clan.  After rot and fire damaged the original pole, it was replaced in 1938 by a duplicate carved by Tlingit craftsmen.  In this photo, taken in October 1899, a large crowd has gathered for the dedication of the totem pole.    Norwegian-born Anders Wilse moved to Seattle in 1890 to work as a surveyor and engineer.  After photographing the building of the Great Northern Railway through the Cascades and working as a cartographer, Wilse turned to commercial photography in 1897. In 1900, Wilse left for a visit to Norway and never returned. (Carolyn J. Marr, "Anders Beer Wilse: Photographer of the Pacific Northwest and Norway."  Columbia 8, no. 4 (Summer 1994): 24-29.)

Title: Hwehlchtid's house at low tide, Shilshole, circa 1903
Notes: Hwehlchtid (called Salmon Bay Charlie by the settlers) of the Shilshole people lived on the southern shore of Salmon Bay, near present-day Ballard, which was then outside of Seattle. Hwehlchtid and his wife Chilohleet'sa (Madeline) remained in their traditional homeland long after others of their tribe had moved away.     This photograph showing Hwehlchtid and Chilohleet’sa’s home, later made into a postcard, was taken at low tide looking west towards Puget Sound. In the early 20th century, Seattle boosters and businesses exploited images of Indigenous people and their culture for sale on postcards or in advertising in order to market the city.     Caption source information: "City of the Changers: Indigenous People and the Transformation of Seattle’s Watersheds," by Coll Thrush, Pacific Historical Review, (2006) Vol. 75, No. 1, pages 89–117, Accessed at http://web.mit.edu/people/spirn/Public/Granite%20Garden%20Research/Urban%20Environmental%20History/Thrush%202006%20Indigenous%20People%20Seattle.pdf

Title: Native camp on the beach, Seattle, circa 1885
Notes: In 1865 the Board of Trustees of Seattle passed Ordinance No. 5 banning Indigenous people from living in the city unless they worked for a non-Indigenous resident and lived on their employer’s property. Despite this attempt to enforce separation between Indigenous people and the settlers, Seattle depended on Indigenous people. Settlers relied on Native people for domestic work and for trade of fish, shellfish, and baskets. Indigenous people from across the Pacific Northwest also harvested hops in agricultural areas to the south and east of Seattle.     This 1880s photo shows a Native encampment in Seattle, probably located near the western end of Bell Street. Because they were excluded from the rest of the city, many Indigenous people camped on the waterfront when visiting or passing through Seattle.

Title: Jack Adams' racing canoe, Portage Bay, Seattle, 1909
Notes: In 1909, Jack Adams (1853-1931), a member of the Suquamish Tribe, built a canoe for a canoe race at Seattle's Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition. Adams built the vessel from a single 48-foot log. On September 6, the canoes raced to the finish line at the foot of the fair's Pay Streak, in Portage Bay. In this photo, Adams and ten other men paddle the canoe on Portage Bay.

Title: Cayuse twin babies in cradleboards, October 2, 1898
Notes: The Cayuse people historically lived in the Blue Mountains of northeastern Oregon and southeastern Washington, where they fish from rivers that flow into the Columbia. They were in an advantageous position between the coast and the Great Plains, allowing them to trade between both. The Cayuse owned horses in large numbers, which led to their expansion and brought them into contact with tribes on the coast as well as further inland. In 1855, the Cayuse in confederation with the Walla Walla and the Umatilla peoples signed a treaty with the United States. The tribes ceded their land but reserved rights to hunt, fish, and gather at usual and accustomed places. They also reserved the Umatilla Indian Reservation as a permanent homeland. Today, most Cayuse live on the Umatilla Indian Reservation.     In this photo, Cayuse twins Tax-a-Lax and Alompum (Emma and Edna Jones) look out from their undecorated wood and fabric cradleboards. One source identifies the twins as grandnieces of Chief Joseph, a leader of the Nez Perce people. Various tribes in interior Washington and Oregon traditionally wrapped their infants tightly and laced them into cradleboards. Cradleboards were often made of wood, with a covering of leather or fabric. Some were quite plain while others were highly decorated with beadwork and shells. Women would carry cradleboards in their arms or on their backs, so they could care for infants while performing other tasks.     From 1889 to 1891, photographer Lee Moorhouse served as “Indian Agent” on the Umatilla Reservation, and many of his subjects were members of the Umatilla, Cayuse, and Walla Walla tribes. Title: Chief Isaac of the Hän, Yukon Territory, circa 1898
Notes: The Hän people historically lived along the Yukon River near the border of eastern Alaska and western Yukon Territory. One of their largest and most important sites was Tr’ochëk, where the Klondike and Yukon Rivers meet. It was there that the Klondike Gold Rush started in 1896 and within a few years thousands of people had come to Hän lands hoping to find gold. The prospectors drove game animals away and took over the land, which threatened the Hän people's traditional lifeways. Chief Isaac of the Hän people, shown here, saw the impacts that the Gold Rush had on his people and their culture. In response, he moved them three miles downriver to Moosehide and entrusted knowledge of many of their songs and dances to Indigenous people in Alaska for safekeeping. In the aftermath of the gold rush, the Hän strove to balance Indigenous traditions against cultural influences from the settlers. Chief Isaac continued to lead the Hän until his death in 1932. Today, most Hän people are part of the Tr’ondëk Hwëch’in First Nation in Dawson City. The Tr’ondëk Hwëch’in began negotiating their Land Claim in 1991 and it came into effect in 1998. Title: Kate Borst christening the steamer "Snoqualmie," August 11, 1919
Notes: In August 1919, the Puget Sound Bridge & Dredging Company launched the steamer "Snoqualmie" at its Seattle shipyard on Harbor Island. The vessel was named for the Snoqualmie Tribe, in honor of the aid they gave the settlers against other Indigenous groups in the war of 1855-1856, now referred to as the Puget Sound War. Many tribal members traveled to Seattle and took part in the launching ceremonies. This photo, taken August 11, 1919, shows Kate Borst (1855-1938) christening the steamer "Snoqualmie" by breaking a bottle of champagne against the bow. Kate Borst was a relative of Chief Si’ahl (Chief Seattle) and the half-sister of Snoqualmie chief Jerry Kanim, who was a nephew of 19th century Snoqualmie chief Patkanim.     Caption information source: "Historic Overview: Carnation, Washington," by Christine Palmer, King County Cultural Resources Division, retrieved from: https://web.archive.org/web/20050519084000/http://www.ci.carnation.wa.us/library/carnation-historical-context.pdf.   Caption information source: "Borst, Kate (1855-1938)" by Alan J. Stein, HistoryLink, retrieved from https://www.historylink.org/File/294.

Title: Indigenous group in ceremonial dress, Seattle, 1931
Notes: This image shows a group of Indigenous people dressed in elaborate ceremonial dress in the summer of 1931. It is possibly in connection with a display of Northwest Indigenous culture at the Seattle Exposition and Outdoor Show, which included a war dance demonstration every evening. The two men on the right wear feather headgear typical of Coast Salish spirit dancers. The man on the left holding a painted drum is Frank Hillaire, a leader of the Lummi people.    Caption information source: "Indian village draws crowds,"  Seattle Post-Intelligencer, July 27, 1931, page 4.

Title: Canoe race at Coupeville festival, August 9, 1936
Notes: In 1936, the Coupeville Indian Water Festival culminated in a race of traditional canoes crewed by Indigenous people from Washington and British Columbia. Eleven canoes started the three-mile race in Penn's Cove on August 9, 1936, but only eight managed to finish. High winds caused three canoes to sink; the Lone Eagle from the Lummi Reservation sank only a few feet from the finish line. Fortunately, no racers were injured and the canoes were undamaged. The winner of the race was Saanich No. 5 from the Saanich Tribe in British Columbia. About 12,000 viewers watched the competition.    Original negative envelope title: "Canoes nearing half-mile point"     Caption information from "Historic Indian race at Coupeville: eleven war canoes in colorful battle," Seattle Post-Intelligencer, Aug. 10, 1936, page 2.

Title: siastenu at the Seattle Post-Intelligencer office, Seattle, November 16, 1940
Notes: siastenu (1857-1958), also named Ruth Sehome Shelton, was born in 1857 on Guemes Island, in one of the last remaining Samish longhouses. She was descended from the Dungeness Klallam, the Lummi, and the Samish peoples. siastenu spread the oral histories of the Coast Salish peoples and carried knowledge of that history into the 20th century. In 1889, siastenu married Wheakadim or Whah-kay-dub (also named William Shelton), who was a leader of the Snohomish people.     This image shows siastenu at the Seattle Post-Intelligencer office on November 16, 1940. She visited the newspaper to deliver a forecast of a cold and harsh winter ahead. While at the PI, siastenu had a conversation in Chinook Jargon with Ed Dalby, the newspaper’s marine editor. Chinook Jargon was a trade language derived from French, English, and several different Indigenous languages. siastenu noted that few white people at that time knew Chinook Jargon and complimented Dalby on his grasp of the language.     Caption information source: "siastenu Ruth Shelton," Tulalip Lushootseed, retrieved from https://tulaliplushootseed.com/dx%CA%B7s%C9%99hubtx%CA%B7-story-tellers/ruth-siast%C9%99nu-shelton/  Caption information source: "'Klonas mika wasa Chinook?' and chief's widow knows the answers," Seattle Post-Intelligencer, Nov. 17, 1940, page 24

Title: Indigenous women making baskets, Olympic Peninsula, 1926
Notes: The women from coastal Washington's Indigenous tribes are known for their basketry. They made twined, coiled, and plaited baskets for gathering clams and berries, storing and serving food, and many other purposes. Basketry techniques were also used for hats and other clothing. At the start of the 20th century, Indigenous artists in the Pacific Northwest were making baskets specifically for the tourist trade and were experimenting with form and design. Making baskets for sale became an import income source for many Indigenous families.     This 1926 photo shows five women making baskets on a beach, possibly at Taholah, in the Quinault Reservation on Washington's Olympic Peninsula. The Quinault are a Coast Salish people whose historic territory was the southwestern Olympic Peninsula.     Caption information source: "Northwest Coast Basketry," by Silvia Koros for the Burke Museum, retrieved from https://www.burkemuseum.org/static/baskets/Teachersguideforbasketry.htm. Chubby, in "Native Peoples of the Olympic Peninsula: Who We Are," by the Olympic Peninsula Intertribal Cultural Advisory Committee, University of Oklahoma Press, 2002, p. 99-106.

Title: Swinomish drummer and singer at the Treaty Day observance, January 22, 1939
Notes: The Swinomish are a Coast Salish group whose historic lands were in the Skagit and Samish River valleys as well as Whidbey, Camano, Fidalgo Islands, and the San Juan Islands. They lived in large permanent villages during the winter, then spread out in spring and summer to gather resources – salmon from the rivers, shellfish from the coastline, cedar wood and berries from inland forests. In 1855, a confederation of four major groups and their allied bands – Aboriginal Swinomish, Lower Skagit, Kikiallus, and Aboriginal Samish – signed the Treaty of Point Elliott with the United States. They ceded their land to the US while reserving rights to hunt, fish, and gather at usual and accustomed places, as well as reserving the Swinomish Reservation on southeastern Fidalgo Island for a permanent homeland. Today, most descendants of these groups live on the Swinomish Reservation.     On January 22, 1939, the tribes living at the Swinomish Reservation near La Conner, Washington, held their annual Treaty Day observance. The event marked the anniversary of the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott. In addition to the tribes from the Swinomish Reservation, tribal members from the Saanich and Cowichan (in British Columbia) and from the Puyallup came to the celebration. Treaty Day events included feasting, singing, drumming, and dancing. The 1939 Treaty Day was the first year that Swinomish chiefs allowed the ceremonies to be photographed. In this photo, Patrick George (seated) beats on a drum while tribal elder Joseph Joe sings.     Caption information source: "Who we are," Swinomish Indian Tribal Community, retrieved from https://swinomish-nsn.gov/who-we-are.aspx  Caption information from "Powwow recalls end of Indian war," by R.C. Cummings, Seattle Post-Intelligencer, Jan. 24, 1939, page 11.

Title: Mr. and Mrs. George Adams standing outside their home, 1939
Notes: The S’Klallam (also spelled Klallam) are a Coast Salish people whose historic lands stretch across the northern Olympic Peninsula from the current location of Port Townsend to the Hoko River, near Makah lands. They also lived on Whidbey Island and on the south shore of Vancouver Island. The S’Klallam lived in permanent longhouses during the winter, but in other seasons individual families spread out and camped at traditional sites to fish, hunt, or gather resources. In 1855, the S’Klallam signed the Point No Point Treaty and ceded their land to the United States but reserved rights to hunt, fish, and gather at usual and accustomed sites. The treaty stated that the S’Klallam would move to a reservation at Skokomish, but this site was distant from their traditional lands and most S’Klallams refused to leave. Beginning in the 1870s, many S’Klallam individuals privately purchased land on their traditional territory. As a result, separate S’Klallam groups emerged, which last to this day. One of the tribes lives on Vancouver Island at Becher Bay. The other three are on the northern Olympic Peninsula – the Lower Elwha Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1939), the Port Gamble S’Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1936), and the Jamestown S’Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1981).    In this 1939 photo, a S’Klallam couple, Mr. and Mrs. George Adams, stand outside their home. The photo was probably taken on the Port Gamble Reservation. MOHAI had previously identified them as Snoqualmie tribe members living on the Tulalip Reservation. Previous version of Notes (6/2023): The traditional home of the Snoqualmie people lay in the Snoqualmie River Valley of western Washington state, between the areas now occupied by the towns of North Bend and Monroe.  Along with the Snohomish and Skykomish, the Snoqualmie lost their lands in the 1855 Treaty of Point Elliott.  Some tribal members who were forced out ot the area moved to the Tulalip Indian Reservation near Marysville.  Others tried to remain in spite of increasing white settlement.  In 1997, the non-reservation Snoqualmie finally gained recognition from the United States government.  In this 1939 photo, an elderly Snoqualmie couple, Mr. and Mrs. George Adams, stand outside their home. The photo was probably taken on the Tulalip Reservation.

Title: Two S'Klallam boys carrying clams on an Olympic Peninsula beach, 1939
Notes: The S’Klallam (also spelled Klallam) are a Coast Salish people whose historic lands stretch across the northern Olympic Peninsula from the current location of Port Townsend to the Hoko River, near Makah lands. They also lived on Whidbey Island and on the south shore of Vancouver Island. The S’Klallam lived in permanent longhouses during the winter, but in other seasons individual families spread out and camped at traditional sites to fish, hunt, or gather resources. In 1855, the S’Klallam signed the Point No Point Treaty and ceded their land to the United States but reserved rights to hunt, fish, and gather at usual and accustomed sites. The treaty stated that the S’Klallam would move to a reservation at Skokomish, but this site was distant from their traditional lands and most S’Klallams refused to leave. Beginning in the 1870s, many S’Klallam individuals privately purchased land on their traditional territory. As a result, separate S’Klallam groups emerged, which last to this day. One of the tribes lives on Vancouver Island at Becher Bay. The other three are on the northern Olympic Peninsula – the Lower Elwha Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1939), the Port Gamble S’Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1936), and the Jamestown S’Klallam Tribe (federally recognized in 1981).    In February 1939, a Seattle Post-Intelligencer photographer took this photo of two Port Gamble S'Klallam boys carrying a bucket of clams at Point Julia. The boy on the left is Claude "Skip" George and on the right is Benny Anderson, Claude's uncle. The dog is George's dog Skipper. Skip George (1930-2011) was raised at Point Julia by grandparents and great-grandparents who spoke the S’Klallam language and passed on memories of S’Klallam culture from the mid-19th century. George went on to become a historian who preserved and passed on knowledge of S'Klallam history and culture. Title: Husky crew and Indigenous canoe race, La Conner, November 29, 1941
Notes: In 1941, Swinomish leader Tandy Wilbur arranged a competition between two Indigenous racing canoes and two shells crewed by the University of Washington Huskies. Wilbur had recently become chairman of the Swinomish Tribal Community, and he intended the race to help form bonds among the several different tribal groups living together on the Swinomish reservation. He also wanted to use publicity from the race to build economic ties to the settler communities around the reservation. The two canoes participating in the race were named 'Lone Eagle' and 'Susie Q.' The four crews made a series of 100-yard sprints down Swinomish Slough, from the Swinomish Reservation to the town of La Conner. When interviewed in the 1990s, members from both sides remembered winning the race.     This image shows three of the racing craft. In the center is a UW shell, with eight rowers, with a Native canoe behind it, with ten rowers. The second UW shell is behind and to the left of the canoe.     Written on negative: Huskies & Indians 1942 [date incorrect]    Caption information source: "The Great Race of 1941: A Coast Salish Public Relations Coup," by Bruce G. Miller, Pacific Northwest Quarterly 89, No. 3 (Summer 1998): 127-135.

Canoe and crew races had a loyal and longstanding following in their respective societies.  However, this race was more of a media event than a true competition, and the association with the championship Husky team gave rare positive coverage to the Swinomish. Title: Indigenous berry pickers on Vashon Island, June 1943
Notes: The United States' entry into World War II in December 1941 created labor shortages as many men left civilian jobs to join the military. On the West Coast, the shortage was exacerbated by the forced removal of Japanese Americans, many of whom were farmers. In the summer of 1943, the Vashon Island Packing Company hired 80 First Nations people from British Columbia to weed and harvest strawberries, loganberries, and currants. The Indigenous workers replaced Filipino workers who were now growing vegetables and working in war industries. The First Nations farmworkers earned 50 to 60 cents an hour, reportedly two to three times what they might have made at home. Those who stayed the whole summer had their transportation to and from Canada paid for as well. Under the 18th century Jay Treaty between Britain and the United States, Indigenous people could freely cross the US-Canada border by proving their tribal status. First Nations people had begun working on Bainbridge and Vashon Islands as fruit pickers in the early 1900s. Most of them were women, because men from their tribes stayed closer to home to work as loggers or dockworkers.    This June 1943 photo shows a group of Indigenous workers, mostly women, in a Vashon Island strawberry field.     Caption information source: "Tribesmen weed berries," by Anne Stewart, Seattle Post-Intelligencer, June 7, 1943, page 11.  Caption information source: Seattle from the Margins, by Megan Asaka, University of Washington Press, pages 153-156.

Title: Charlie Swan, Makah cultural leader, Neah Bay, August 1945
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     In August of each year the Makah people hold the annual Makah Days celebration at Neah Bay, which celebrates the Makah people gaining full US citizenship in 1924. In their 1945 festival, the Makah also celebrated the end of World War II, the imminent return of 45 tribal members serving in the military, and the dedication of a new housing project on the reservation. Tribal leader Charlie Swan, whose son served in the Pacific, led the dancing. In this August photo, Swan wears a button blanket and wooden mask, and he holds a painted drum. Swan, who was well known for his dancing, had a dance troupe which gave performances throughout the Pacific Northwest.     Caption information source: Makah Tribe website at https://makah.com  Caption information from "Neah Bay Indians hold celebration," by Anne Stewart, Seattle Post-Intelligencer, Aug. 28, 1945, p. 11.

Title: Slahal game at the Swinomish smokehouse, January 22, 1946
Notes: The January 22, 1946 Treaty Day celebration at the Swinomish Reservation at La Conner featured the gambling game known as slahal or the bone game.  Two teams of players sat in lines  facing one another, with one player holding the pair of   bones and the others singing and beating time with sticks   and a drum.  This photograph shows one line of players.    Abel D. Joe of Swinomish sits to the left of a group of tall scoring sticks placed in the ground.  He chants while   holding one of the game bones in his open hand.  Two   drummers sit to the left; other players sing and drum the   floor with sticks.

Title: Indigenous dancers fancy dancing at the Ellensburg Rodeo, September 1945
Notes: The first rodeo at Ellensburg, Washington, opened in September 1923. For many years, the "Indian Village" was one of the more popular attractions at the rodeo. There, Indigenous people from many tribes camped in teepees and put on dancing and riding performances. In 1945, 100 Yakama Natives camped and performed at the rodeo and rode in its parades.     In this 1945 photo, young dancers from an unidentified tribe demonstrate fancy dancing at the rodeo. The fancy dance, also called the Oklahoma Feather Dance, was invented in the early 20th century by Gus McDonald, a member of the Ponca tribe in Oklahoma. It evolved from earlier Indigenous dance traditions and has been performed by people from many different Indigenous tribes at celebrations and competitions.     Caption information from John Ludtka, The Tradition Lives: a 75 year history of the Ellensburg Rodeo (1998 : Ellensburg, Wash.).  Caption information source: "The Native American Fancy Dance," National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum, retrieved from https://nationalcowboymuseum.org/explore/the-native-american-fancy-dance/

Title: Indigenous people on the beach at Port Townsend, September 2, 1899
Notes: Port Townsend, site of a S’Klallam village prior to the arrival of settlers in the mid-1800s, became an important trading center by the end of the 19th century. Indigenous peoples from Canada and the tribes of Puget Sound and the Olympic Peninsula gathered along the shores of Port Townsend Bay to trade and socialize. Many also stopped here on their way to or from Puget Sound, including for seasonal work in the hop fields south and east of Seattle. In this photograph, canoes line the beach and tents are pitched above the high tide line.

Title: Indigenous group launching their canoe at Port Townsend, August 30, 1899
Notes: Many Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest traditionally carve canoes from cedar. The canoes are made in several styles and sizes, and the larger ocean-going canoes required multiple people to launch. This image taken in late August 1899 shows a group of Indigenous people dragging a cedar dugout canoe towards the waters of Port Townsend Bay. In the late 19th century, many Indigenous people traveled to Port Townsend to conduct trade on the beach. Canoes were often landed backwards, with the prow facing the water, in order to facilitate the next launching. In areas of frequent launchings and landings, the people cleared the beach rocks away, leaving open "canoe runs," some of which can still be seen on certain Olympic Peninsula beaches.     This canoe is of the West Coast style, as seen by its upturned prow made to resemble a wolf head. West Coast style canoes were first created by the Nuu-chah-nulth peoples of Vancouver Island, but they were adopted by many Indigenous groups across the Pacific Northwest because they were more suited to traveling in rougher waters and open ocean.     Caption information source: "Canoes, Lifeways, Waterways, "Simon Fraser University, retrieved from https://www.sfu.ca/archaeology/museum/exhibits/virtual-exhibits/canoes--lifeways--waterways.html

He moved to Port Townsend, on the Olympic Peninsula, in 1897, where he worked for the customs service and frequently went on photographic trips with local banker/photographer James McCurdy.  Wilcox moved to California in 1916 but returned to the Pacific Northwest in 1924.  He died in 1940.  (Bob Cole, "William Holmes Wilcox: Amateur Photographer as Artist."  Portage 2, no. 1 (Fall/Winter 1980-81):4-9.)

Title: Group of Indigenous people at Port Townsend, August 30, 1899
Notes: Port Townsend, site of a S’Klallam village prior to the arrival of settlers in the mid-1800s, became an important trading center by the end of the 19th century. Indigenous peoples from Canada and the tribes of Puget Sound and the Olympic Peninsula gathered along the shores of Port Townsend Bay to trade and socialize. Many also stopped here on their way to or from Puget Sound, including for seasonal work in the hop fields south and east of Seattle.     In this scene, a woman weaves a basket amid the hustle and bustle of a crowded camp. In the background, a white man examines a small box, perhaps intending to buy or trade. Baskets were among the top trade items for the Makah and other Indigenous peoples of the Olympic Peninsula region.

Title: Makah dancing at Colman Dock, Seattle, March 22, 1941
Notes: The Makah people of the northwest tip of the Olympic Peninsula refer to themselves as Kwih-dich-chuh-ahtx, which translates roughly to "the people who live by the rocks and seagulls." The early Makah were skilled mariners, using several types of canoes which they carved from western red cedar for various purposes—war, whaling, fishing, sealing, carrying cargo, and long voyages. Today, roughly 1400 Makah live in and around their traditional lands near Neah Bay on the Makah Indian Reservation. The carving of their skilled woodworkers can range in size from tiny masks to totems and giant, oceangoing canoes. Whaling and fishing have been central to Makah culture for thousands of years. The Makah are the only tribe to be granted whaling rights by treaty with the US government, in the Treaty of Neah Bay signed in 1855. While the Makah voluntarily suspended whale hunting in the 1920s due to the near extinction of whales from commercial whaling, they exercised their treaty right to hunt whales once in 1999 before court decisions blocked further legal hunting.     Here five members of the Makah tribe gave a preview of their upcoming dance performance upon arriving at Colman Dock on March 22, 1941. Charlie Swan (at right, with mask), his wife, and his daughter Delores are shown with Alexander Green (playing the drum) and his wife. The group came to Seattle to attend a Chamber of Commerce luncheon promoting tourism to the Olympic Peninsula. Charlie (also spelled Charley) Swan was a chief of the Makah. He was well known for his dancing, and had a dance troupe which gave performances throughout the Pacific Northwest.    Written on negative: Neah Bay Indians    Caption information source: "Indians DO give a whoop for Seattle," by Doug Welch, Seattle Post-Intelligencer, Mar. 28, 1941, part 2, page 1. Title: Chief Jerry Kanim and his family, Snoqualmie, February 21, 1948
Notes: The Snoqualmie people are a Coast Salish group who have lived in the Snoqualmie River Valley since time immemorial. They made dugout canoes which they used to navigate the river and reach Puget Sound. Traditionally the Snoqualmie burned off the bottom lands of the Snoqualmie Valley to create open areas that ensured an abundance of edible plants for foraging as well as supplied space for game animals to feed. In the early 19th century, the Snoqualmie were among the most powerful tribes around Puget Sound. They exerted economic influence over neighboring groups from Whidbey Island to Snoqualmie Pass. Snoqualmie chief Patkanim (also spelled Pat Kanim) signed the Treaty of Point Elliott in 1855, ceding the Snoqualmie people’s land to the United States. They were temporarily assigned to live on the Tulalip reservation and were promised a reservation of their own. However, the US government reneged on its promise and no land was allocated for the Snoqualmie, most of whom moved back to their historic lands or stayed on the Tulalip reservation. The Snoqualmie finally received a reservation on their historic land in 1999.    This image shows Snoqualmie chief Jerry Kanim (the nephew of Patkanim) with some of his family members. On February 21, 1948, Jerry Kanim and representatives of several other tribes met at Eagles Hall in Carnation, Washington, on historic Snoqualmie land to discuss ways of pressing their claims to the reservation land that had been promised to them.     [SHS 15,662]    Caption information source: "Indians still awaiting '80 acres per family'", Seattle Post-Intelligencer, February 22, 1948, page 7

Title: Women cooking salmon, Muckleshoot Reservation, circa 1950
Notes: The Muckleshoot Indian Tribe is made up of descendants of the Duwamish and Upper Puyallup peoples who lived near Puget Sound and its associated waterways since time immemorial. Muckleshoot ancestors lived in villages that were tied together by marriage bonds, trade, shared ceremonies, and use of the same land. This network of interconnected villages extended far beyond the Upper Puyallup and Duwamish tribes, which allowed Muckleshoot ancestors to fish, hunt, and gather across a large area, from the west side of Puget Sound to the Cascade Mountains. The Upper Puyallup and Duwamish tribes signed treaties in 1854 and 1855 respectively, which ceded their land to the United States in exchange for reserving rights to hunt, fish, and gather at usual and accustomed places. The tribes were also promised reservations as permanent homelands. A conflict between the settlers and several Indigenous groups, now called the Puget Sound War, occurred from 1855-56 and in its aftermath a reservation was established on a plain called Muckleshoot at the junction of the White and Green Rivers. After the Muckleshoot Reservation was established, its people gradually came to be known as the Muckleshoot Tribe, instead of by their historical tribal affiliations. Since the early 20th century, the Muckleshoot people have defended their treaty rights, especially fishing rights.     Salmon was historically a mainstay food for the Indigenous tribes of the Pacific Northwest and has remained an important part of their diet. The catching, preparing, and cooking of salmon also remain significant parts of the culture of many Indigenous peoples in Washington. In this photo, several women on the Muckleshoot Reservation help prepare salmon, which has been cut and strung onto sticks and then suspended over an open fire to grill. The wood is probably alder, which gives a distinctive flavor to fresh-cooked salmon and was the preferred fuel.     Caption information source: "History of the Muckleshoot Indian Tribe and its Reservation," Muckleshoot Indian Tribe, retrieved from http://www.muckleshoot.nsn.us/about-us/overview.aspx.

Title: Native Alaskan woman working on a canoe by a river, circa 1909

Title: Tlingit boy wearing a woven hat, Sitka, circa 1915
Notes: The Tlingit people have lived on the coast and islands of what is now southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. Tlingit society is organized into clans, which follow maternal descent. Fishing, gathering, and hunting were central to historic Tlingit lifeways. They used salmon, shellfish, seals, berries, deer, and other food sources, making sure to use every part for different purposes, not wasting anything. The Tlingit also had many uses for cedar trees, from houses, to totems and baskets. Cedar was also used for canoes, which were one of the main modes of transport for the Tlingit and enabled them to travel and trade not only amongst each other but also with neighboring peoples north and south along the Pacific coast.     This young Tlingit boy is photographed in a photographer's studio wearing a blanket and a woven spruce root hat typical of the northern Northwest Coast Indigenous peoples. The spruce root is twined so tightly that it sheds water, and the hat's rim is decorated with a geometric pattern.    Caption information source: "Our History," Central Council Tlingit and Haida Indian Tribes of Alaska, retrieved from http://www.ccthita.org/about/history/index.html

Title: Tal Tan Billy, Alaska, circa 1898 - 1920
Notes: The Tlingit are a group of Indigenous peoples whose traditional home is on the coast of southeastern Alaska. The Tlingit, as well as neighboring groups, weave elaborate ceremonial blankets with abstracted images of animals. The blankets are called Chilkat blankets after one of the Tlingit tribes, and are traditionally worn during important events.    The man in this photograph wears a woven Chilkat blanket and a wooden headdress carved with the image of a bear. His name, written on the photograph as Tal Tan Billy, implies that he was connected with the Tahltan people who lived inland from the British Columbia coast, along the Stikine River. The subject's ceremonial clothing is typical of the Tlingit; Tahltan artwork was influenced by Tlingit styles. The Tahltan and Tlingit peoples had a complex relationship that involved trade networks, intermarriage, and some overlapping territories.    Caption on image: "Tal Tan Billy" ; "J.E.W." Title: Chief Anotklosh of the Taku, Alaska, circa 1913
Notes: The Tlingit people have lived on the coast and islands of what is now southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. Tlingit society is organized into clans, which follow maternal descent. Fishing, gathering, and hunting were central to historic Tlingit lifeways – they used salmon, shellfish, seals, berries, deer, and other food sources. They used every part for different purposes, not wasting anything. The Tlingit also had many uses for cedar trees, from houses to totems, canoes, and baskets. Canoes were one of the main modes of transport for the Tlingit and enabled them to travel and trade not only amongst each other but also with neighboring peoples north and south along the Pacific coast.     The Taku are a tribe of northern Tlingit whose traditional lands extended along the Taku River and included the area northeast of Juneau, Alaska. The northern Tlingit traded heavily with merchant vessels and bartered for large numbers of imported goods. In this image, Chief Anotklosh (also spelled 'Ano-Thlosh' or 'Ano-Tlosh'), chief of the Taku, wears a woven Chilkat blanket made from cedar bark and mountain goat wool which had been dyed yellow, black and blue-green. He holds a carved wooden bird rattle and wears a European military-style cap. Chilkat blankets, named after one of the Tlingit tribes, are elaborate ceremonial blankets made by the Tlingit as well as neighboring peoples. They feature abstracted images of animals and are traditionally worn during important events.     Caption on image: ""Chief Anotklosk Chief of the Taku Tribe, Juneau, Alaska."" Title: Tlingit man and woman in full potlatch costumes, Alaska, 1906
Notes: The Tlingit people have lived on the coast and islands of what is now southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. Tlingit society is organized into clans, which follow maternal descent. Fishing, gathering, and hunting were central to historic Tlingit lifeways – they used salmon, shellfish, seals, berries, deer, and other food sources. They used every part for different purposes, not wasting anything. The Tlingit also had many uses for cedar trees, from houses, to totems, canoes, and baskets. Canoes were one of the main modes of transport for the Tlingit and enabled them to travel and trade not only amongst each other but also with neighboring peoples north and south along the Pacific coast.    The two Tlingit people in this photograph wear elaborate painted and beaded tunics. The man (left) wears a tall hat topped with rings which signify the number of potlatches he has given. He holds a painted paddle with a fringe of deer hoof rattles. The woman (right) wears a nose ring and a bear claw headdress. She carries a crescent-shaped object painted with a raven design. Both individuals wear face paint. The woman is identified as Kaw-claa in another photograph in the museum's collection. Potlatches are traditional feasts involving extensive gift-giving as a show of power and wealth. Potlatches are a traditional part of many Northwest Coast Indigenous cultures.     Caption on image: "Natives in full potlatch dancing custome [sic]. Copyright 1906 by Case & Draper."     The name of photographer Frank Nowell is embossed on the lower right corner of the image. Nowell likely copied the original Case & Draper photograph. Title: Three brothers, headmen of the Chilkat, Alaska, 1907
Notes: The Chilkat are a Tlingit tribe who have lived in and around their village of Klukwan on the Chilkat River, in southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. They lived on foods available on their lands as well as trading with other tribes on the Pacific coast and inland. Settlers came to Chilkat lands in large numbers in the early 20th century, and they dispossessed the Chilkat of most of their land. US authorities attempted to suppress Chilkat culture by prohibiting potlatches and other traditional customs. However, their efforts failed and the Chilkat people maintained many of their traditions. Today most Chilkat people live in Klukwan.     This image shows three brothers and leaders of the Kak-Von-Tons, a part of the Chilkat tribe. They are identified as Ka-sh-ak (also spelled Kaalgéi), Skan-doo (Skundoo or Sx'andu.oo), and Ind-a-yanek (Swatka or Yindayáank') and they pose together wearing their ceremonial clothing. Two of the brothers have elaborately patterned Chilkat blankets, and the third wears a shirt decorated with deer hoofs. The man in the center also displays a carved wooden bird helmet with feathers attached. Each man holds a carved and painted bird-shaped rattle.     Caption on image: "Three brothers, old head-men of the Kak-von-tons of the Chilkat Tribe. Ka-Sh-Ak, the Monkey-Man; Skan-Doo, notorious old medicene [sic] man; Ind-A-Yanek (Swatka) the famous Indian guide" ; "Copyright 1907 by Case & Draper."    Caption information source: "History," Chilkat Indian Village, retrieved from https://chilkat-nsn.gov/history/  Caption information source: "Ka-Sh-Ak, the Monkeyman. Title: Chilkat people in dance costumes, Klukwan, Alaska, circa 1895
Notes: The Chilkat are a Tlingit tribe who have lived in and around their village of Klukwan on the Chilkat River, in southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. They lived on foods available on their lands as well as trading with other tribes on the Pacific coast and inland. Settlers came to Chilkat lands in large numbers in the early 20th century, and they dispossessed the Chilkat of most of their land. US authorities attempted to suppress Chilkat culture by prohibiting potlatches and other traditional customs. However, their efforts failed and the Chilkat people maintained many of their traditions. Today most Chilkat people live in Klukwan.     The costumes worn by these Chilkat dancers at Klukwan include button-design and beaded tunics, with elaborately-beaded aprons and fringed leather shirts. The boy in the darker costume wears a wig and headdress of mountain goat horn normally reserved for the ixt, or spiritual leader. All five of the men have nose rings, a traditional adornment, but the boys do not wear them.     Caption on image: "Chilkat Indians in dancing costumes, Alaska" ; "Copyright by Winter & Pond."    Caption information source: "History," Chilkat Indian Village, retrieved from https://chilkat-nsn.gov/history/

Title: Tlingit women weaving baskets, Alaska, circa 1897
Notes: The Tlingit people have lived on the coast and islands of what is now southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. Tlingit society is organized into clans, which follow maternal descent. Fishing, gathering, and hunting were central to historic Tlingit lifeways – they used salmon, shellfish, seals, berries, deer, and other food sources. They used every part for different purposes, not wasting anything. The Tlingit also had many uses for cedar trees, from houses to totems, canoes, and baskets. Canoes were one of the main modes of transport for the Tlingit and enabled them to travel and trade not only amongst each other but also with neighboring peoples north and south along the Pacific coast.     Tlingit women made finely-woven baskets for the tourist trade and marketed them in towns served by steamship lines. In this photo, three weavers work on baskets using spruce root and grasses, and decorated in a technique known as "false embroidery." False embroidery involves using dyed grass stems wrapped around the weft so the pattern shows only on the outside of the basket. Beaded pouches, a basketry-covered flask, and a few other items are laid out on the grass in front of the women. A baby sleeps beside its mother, wrapped tightly in its cradleboard, and a glass baby bottle with a long-necked nipple sits at the cradleboard's foot.     Caption on image: "Native women weaving baskets, Alaska. Copyright by Winter & Pond."    Caption information source: "Our History," Central Council Tlingit and Haida Indian Tribes of Alaska, retrieved from http://www.ccthita.org/about/history/index.html

Title: Infant asleep in a sling, Alaska, circa 1905
Notes: In this image, an infant wearing a cap covered with buttons sleeps in a birchbark sling rigged with a rocking mechanism. Around the beginning of the 20th century, white photographers used photographs of Indigenous babies on commercial products, and this image was produced on a Christmas card.     Caption on cardboard photo mount: "Alaska slumberland."

Title: Group of Chilkat people in traditional dance costumes, Klukwan, Alaska, circa 1895
Notes: The Chilkat are a Tlingit tribe who have lived in and around their village of Klukwan on the Chilkat River, in southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. They lived on foods available on their lands as well as trading with other tribes on the Pacific coast and inland. Settlers came to Chilkat lands in large numbers in the early 20th century, and they dispossessed the Chilkat of most of their land. US authorities attempted to suppress Chilkat culture by prohibiting potlatches and other traditional customs. However, their efforts failed and the Chilkat people maintained many of their traditions. Today most Chilkat people live in Klukwan.     Here, men and boys dressed in dance regalia pose in front of the house of Chief Klart-Reech at Klukwan, Alaska. The man in the center, wearing the highly-patterned Chilkat tunic, is Yielgooxu, a hereditary chief of the Klukwan Whale House. The man next to him wears a fur-trimmed shirt with a beaver design. Several of the masks and spruce root hats appear in photos of the interior of the Whale House taken by the same photographer. The mixture of native and European clothing is typical of this time period.    Caption on image: "Ixterior [sic] of chief's house. Chilkat Indians in old dancing costumes, Alaska. Copyright Winter & Pond."    Caption information source: "History," Chilkat Indian Village, retrieved from https://chilkat-nsn.gov/history/

Title: Woman weaving a Chilkat blanket, Alaska, circa 1904
Notes: The Chilkat are a Tlingit tribe who have lived in and around their village of Klukwan on the Chilkat River, in southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. They lived on foods available on their lands as well as trading with other tribes on the Pacific coast and inland. Settlers came to Chilkat lands in large numbers in the early 20th century, and they dispossessed the Chilkat of most of their land. US authorities attempted to suppress Chilkat culture by prohibiting potlatches and other traditional customs. However, their efforts failed and the Chilkat people maintained many of their traditions. Today most Chilkat people live in Klukwan.     In this photograph, a woman works on a Chilkat ceremonial dance blanket using a frame loom. Chilkat blankets are elaborate ceremonial blankets made by the Tlingit as well as neighboring peoples. They feature abstracted images of animals and are traditionally worn during important events. The warp threads, made from cedar bark covered with mountain goat wool, hang in bundles from the top bar. The weaver has completed the border on three sides and is beginning to weave the design in the center. She has carefully placed newspapers over the edges of her blanket to protect the finished portion. A closer look at the image reveals that the newspapers originated in California and are dated January 12, 1904. Traditionally, men created the designs and painted them on boards which the women used as patterns for their weaving.     Caption information source: "History," Chilkat Indian Village, retrieved from https://chilkat-nsn.gov/history/   Caption information source: "Unpacking a phrase: The Chilkat blanket," by Christy Christodoulides, Burke Museum, retrieved from https://www.burkemuseum.org/news/unpacking-phrase-chilkat-blanket

Title: Indigenous women merchants at Treadwell Mines on Douglas Island, Alaska, circa 1898 - 1912
Notes: The Tlingit people have lived on the coast and islands of what is now southeastern Alaska since time immemorial. Tlingit society is organized into clans, which follow maternal descent. Fishing, gathering, and hunting were central to historic Tlingit lifeways – they used salmon, shellfish, seals, berries, deer, and other food sources. They used every part for different purposes, not wasting anything. The Tlingit also had many uses for cedar trees, from houses, to totems, canoes, and baskets. Canoes were one of the main modes of transport for the Tlingit and enabled them to travel and trade not only amongst each other but also with neighboring peoples north and south along the Pacific coast.     This image shows a group of Indigenous women selling baskets, beaded clothing, and other goods near the Treadwell gold mines. The Treadwell mines were located on Douglas Island, across the channel from Juneau. The land around Juneau is the traditional home of the Auke and Taku tribes of the Tlingit people. In 1881, settlers and gold miners displaced the Auke and Taku people in order to establish the Treadwell gold mines. After the mines opened, Indigenous women came from nearby villages to sell wares to the gold miners and tourists. The baskets for sale in this photograph are Tlingit in style.     Caption on image: "Indian merchants at Treadwell Mines"    Caption information source: "Our History," Central Council Tlingit and Haida Indian Tribes of Alaska, retrieved from http://www.ccthita.org/about/history/index.html

He was active in Seattle and beginning in 1898, made around 100 trips to Alaska and the Yukon. La Roche retired in 1912 and died in Sedro-Wooley, Washington in the 1930s. Title: Skitswish Mission of the Sacred Heart, Cataldo, Idaho, ca. 1920
Notes: Mission building; six pillars hold up the arched roof-front with sunburst circular window.    Note from unidentified source: Old Mission State Park features the oldest standing building in Idaho, The Mission of the Sacred Heart built between 1848 and 1853. Mission walls stand a foot thick, without the benefit of nails. The structure was woven carefully of straw, mud and wooden pegs. Inside, there are no pews because the Indians preferred to worship in an open room. Over 300 members of the tribe labored over the construction. It transferred in 1877 to Desmet where it stands today.    Photo from Don. B. Scott, former editor of Coeur d'Alene Press - his father had this photo taken about 1920.
Subjects: Sacred Heart Mission (Cataldo, Idaho); Skitswish Indians--Spiritual life; Missions--Idaho

Title: Sinkiuse-Columbia chief Moses, his nephew Chil-Lee-Leet-Sah and two other delegates sent to petition President Hayes, Washington, ca. 1879
Notes: Four men pose for portrait in suits; two seated, two standing.    Caption on mount: This is a deputation of Indian Chiefs that General [Oliver Otis] Howard sent back to Washington D.C. in about 1879 or 1880. The clothes they are wearing was the idea of the Army Officers that conducted them on the trip. The man at the extreme left (sitting) is Chief Moses. The tall man standing next with his right hand on the shoulder of Chief Moses is Chil-lee-leet-sah, a nephew of Chief Moses and at the time the picture was taken had been designated to be the successor of Chief Moses. The large man sitting next is an Umatilla chief named Peo-peo-mox-mox which appears to mean Flying Yellow Geese. The small man standing at the extreme right is an Umatilla or Cayuse chief named as follows: Kah-lees-quot-quo-lot. Chief Moses died late in March 1899 and Chil-lee-leet-sah was drowned in the Coulmbia river near the mouth of the Spokane river about a year before Chief Moses died. We have no record of the other two chiefs.    Note from Center for Columbia River History: 1879 delegation to Washington D.C. Left to Right, Chief Moses (Sulktalthscosum), Moses' nephew, Chillileetsah, Hiachenie of the Cayuse, and Chief Homily of the Walla Wallas.
Subjects: Moses, Chief, ca. 1829-1899; Chil-Lee-Leet-Sah; Group portraits--Washington (State); Sinkiuse-Columbia Indians; Umatilla Indians; Cayuse Indians; Walla Walla Indians; Delegations--Washington (D.C.)

Title: Nez Perce woman named Tolah, Camas Prairie, Idaho, ca. 1899
Notes: Studio portrait of woman seated with hands folded.  She is bare headed, wears a loose blouse and blanket.  Tolah is the friendly Nez Perce woman who warned the whites in 1877.  She is the sister of Chief Mox Mox, leader of the active field Indians, Camas Prairie in Idaho.  Lake Tolo is named after her.  She is also Emma Broncheau's grandmother.

Title: Nez Perce rodeo champion Jackson Sundown poses with horse
Notes: Man wearing a wide-brimmed hat, beaded gauntlets, shirt, jeans & spurred boots stands holding horse by its bridle. In background can be seen people moving about and a concession stand.    Note from unidentifed source: Jackson Sundown [1863 - 1923], model for Charles Russell.  [His family joined Chief Joseph in his flight of 1877. They crossed into Canada after the  defeat at Bear Paw, Mont. Eventually, about 1910, Sundown and his wife returned to Nez  Perce country. He won the titles of world champion saddle bronc rider and rodeo performer of the year at the 1916 Pendleton, Ore., Roundup - at the age of 53]

Notes: Group of people moving about on steps of a dilapidated single-story building    Note from unidentified source: The Kalispel schoolhouse, classroom and living quarters for the teacher and family. Title: Kalispel home, Kalispel Indian Reservation, Washington, 1985
Notes: Single-story home set under trees; tepee visible beyond parked car. Small child sits on the doorstep.    Note from unidentified source: Under provisions of the 'Family Plan' for use of judgement fund, many Kalispel built modern homes on and off the reservation. Title: Grand Coulee Region exploratory group, ca. 1920s
Notes: Eleven men from Princeton University and University of Chicago are seen studying the Grand Coulee Region in the area of Adrian, west of Soap Lake.  Dr. Harlen Bretz, of University of Chicago, brought a student group from Princeton and the Uchicago to study Grand Coulee.  These studies over many years led to the "Bretz Flood" explanation of the Columbia River and Channeled Scablands.

Title: Cayuse/Nez Perce man known as Tauitau  or Tu Ah Tway poses with headdress and other beaded objects
Notes: Studio portrait of seated man with feathers in his hair, spotted shirt with armbands, blanket across lap & fur around neck. Set next to him are a beaded, feathered headdress, a widebrimmed hat with beaded band, a pipe, a wide-beaded collar and other objects. Painted backdrop of tree is behind him.     Note from unidentified source: Tu-Ah-Tway or 'Young Chief' as he was also known. He was a son of Allicot [Ollokot], the brother of Chief Joseph. His mother was a descendent of the famous Cayuse chief Tauitowe (as the name appears in the old histories) also called Young Chief, who was prominent in Dr. Whitman's day, also during the Cayuse War and at Gov. Stevens Walla Walla council. This man died about 1920. On account of his lineage and his personality his memory is much revered among the Umatillas and Nez Perces of the Chief Joseph strain.
Subjects: Tauitau; Joseph, Nez Perce Chief, 1840-1904--Family; Portraits--Oregon; Nez Perce Indians--Clothing & dress; Cayuse Indians--Clothing & dress; Nez Perce Indians--Arts & crafts; Cayuse Indians--Arts & crafts

Title: Colville writing by teenager named Fannie Wynecoop writing, Fort Spokane, Washington
Notes: This may have been some kind of test.  It was written by a 17 year old Colville girl.    List compiled by Fannie  Wynecoop entitled: What to do in case of accidents.  The   text reads:  1. For nose bleeds put ice or anything as cold  as you can get just back of the neck.  Roll a small piece of paper up and place under the upper lip.  Hold the arms as   high above the head as possible and make the patient hold   his head up.  2.  For frost bite rub snow on the injured   part and do not go near a fire or in a warm room.  3. For   sprained ankles or any other joints keep hot cloths on the   injured part and if you can't get a doctor try to get it in  place as soon as possible.  4. For sun stroke keep the head  cool the same as in nose bleeds and do not give anything   cold to drink but give something warm.  5. In case of   fainting give the patient plenty of fresh air and loosen all tight clothing, sprinkle a little cold water on face. 6. In  case of apoplexy keep the head up.  7. In case of a   hemmorage of any kind to keep quiet is the main thing.  8.   For cuts of any kind keep everything clean to avoid puss   gathering.  For a bad cut on the arm for instance bind tight with a stout string or cloth above the cut.
Subjects: First aid in illness and injury; Colville Indians--Health  & welfare; Health education--Washington (State)--Fort   Spokane

Repository: Northwest Museum of Arts and Culture

Title: Kutenai people that attended conference with Capt. John Webster, Bonner's Ferry, Idaho, May 31, 1911
Notes: Thirtyeight people who attended a meeting between the Kootenai and Capt. John Webster, U.S. Indian Agent, pose in front of a building.  The meeting was held at Bonner's Ferry in the A.J. Kents Real Estate Office.  Mr. kent was acting on behald of the Kootenais so the government could build a school for them.  The chief of the Kootenais from 1900-1916, Isidore Chiquiet held the meeting with Capt. Webster, an agent of the Colville Indian Agency, Colville Indian Reservation.  In order to have the school built, Chiquiet agreed to have his tribe enrolled under the Colville Agency. Title: Yakama/Umatilla Chief Shet-a-mo-on-e, Washington, ca. 1900
Notes: Shet-a-mo-on-e, a noted Yakama chief stands  holding pipe, wearing horned headdress, decorated tunic & leggings, beaded moccasins; photographed standing in front of buffalo-skin tepee. Same man in NA611    Caption on image: 'Shet-a-mo-on-e'.  A noted chief of Yakimas. Copyrighted by Rutter. 1900. The Tepee is buffalo skins.    Note on verso of photograph: Shut-a-mo-ne, Sheep Cross Horns. This Indian is half Yakima and half Umatilla. His uncle was an Umatilla Chief. He served with U.S. Troops during the Bannock war of 1878, and killed the Bannock chief, and brought his head back to the camp of General Howard. He prevented the Umatillas from joining the hostiles and Bannocks in war against the whites. He dies several years ago, and at the big potlatch his war horse and nearly all his belongings were given to Shut-a-mo-ne, his nephew, he being the nearest living relative. It is the Umatilla Chief's dress that is now worn by Shut-a-mo-ne as shown in this picture.

Title: Tlingit totem pole is unveiled at Pioneer Square, Seattle, Washington, October 18, 1899
Notes: A large crowd waits in Pioneer Square for the dedication of the totem pole, 1899. The pole stands beside an intersection, and is surrounded by people and stands for a fireworks display. Wagons, trolley car and buildings of Pioneer Square visible in background. Viewed from east.     Caption on image: Unveiling the totem pole on Pioneer Square, Seattle, Oct 18, '99    Note from Museum of History and Industry: The totem pole at Pioneer Square has been a Seattle landmark since 1899. That year, a group of Seattle businessmen visited a Tlingit village in Alaska. They thought the village was deserted and removed a 50-foot tall  totem pole as a souvenir. The men brought the pole back to Seattle and had it set up in Pioneer Square. They were later fined for the theft of the pole. After being damaged by fire in 1938, it was replaced by a duplicate pole carved by Tlingit craftsmen.    PH Coll 285.64

Title: Two Nez Perce women, identified as sisters, Colville Indian Reservation, Washington, ca. 1900-1910.
Notes: Two young women sit on chairs dressed with earrings, necklaces, moccasins. They each hold cornhusk bags.      Caption on negative sleeve:  Two squaws with beadwork.    Note from unidentified source:  Two sisters holding cornhusk bags, probably Nez Perce.    Note from researcher: These are the daughters of Jim Billy and his wife Yumatwy (Eyomotwy). They are Alpiato Billy (Billie) aka Alpiato or Alice Waters aka Wash-e-tone-my and Annie Billy (Billie) aka Yupchasin or Upchasin aka Wa-hem-pum. They are my paternal grand-aunts - sisters to my grandfather, Tom Billy. There is at least one other picture of them together. Alpiato is the mother of Art Circle (Art's father was  Charlie Wilpocken), who is also in some of the pictures in your collection.

Title: Tlingit totem poles, canoes and a Chilkat blanket on display at Sheldon Jackson Museum, Sitka, Alaska, n.d.
Notes: Chilkat blanket, totem poles, canoes, tools, baskets & nets  on display. The Chilkat robe is said to be from Killisnoo from the gravesite of a man who had adopted to Christianity and vowed to give up old customs. The robe with "Diving Whale Pattern", was donated to the museum by his family. Also pictured are two totem poles from Metlakatla that were brought to the museum in 1888 when a group of young men from Father Duncan's Christian community came to the Sitka Industrial Training School. They were about to burn the poles when Sheldon Jackson arrived to bring the young men to Sitka and asked them to spare the poles and bring them to the museum.    Note from unidentified source: In Sheldon Jackson Museum    PH Coll 587.7

These things belong to Shakes and to the Kiksuddy.  I have notes on numbered articles.  Information Tom Ukase, 3/4, 1950.    Note from unidentified source:  Possessions of Chief Shakes displayed in his house, Wrangell; carved masks, paddles, boxes, button blankets, shirt, copper, with Shakes seated on platform.    Note from researcher Meda DeWitt Schleifman, 9/2011:  [Regarding a] request for fixing an error on a photo of my Grandfather and Clan possessions. You have the items in the photo as owned by the Kiksuddy. THESE ARE UNDER THE OWNERSHIP OF THE NAANYA.AYI' Which is the clan of Chief Shakes and the Shakes title.        In Garfield Volume 10, leaf 51

Title: Yakama/Umatilla Chief Shet-a-mo-on-e, Spokane, Washington, ca. 1900
Notes: Man in ceremonial dress poses in studio, in front of painted backdrop, ca. 1900. He is holding pipe & bag, and wearing horned headdress, plain shirt, decorated leggings, plain breechcloth. Same man in NA628    Note on verso of NA628: Shut-a-mo-ne, Sheep Cross Horns. This Indian is half Yakima and half Umatilla. His uncle was an Umatilla Chief. He served with U.S. Troops during the Bannock war of 1878, and killed the Bannock chief, and brought his head back to the camp of General Howard. He prevented the Umatillas from joining the hostiles and Bannocks in war against the whites. He died several years ago, and at the big potlatch his war horse and nearly all his belongings were given to Shut-a-mo-ne, his nephew, he being the nearest living relative.    PH Coll 287.15

Title: Tlingit totem pole in front of wooden structure, Wrangell, Alaska
Notes: On verso of image:  Totem at Wrangell. Picture given to Viola E. Garfield by Mrs. J.W. Young, Ketchikan 8/12/40.  This pole was owned by A. Rasmussen, Skagway. See Niblack, Coast Indians, Plate LXV, fig. 347.  The top figure is beaver and not the bear. Rasmussen says the three figures below the beaver were carved separately and nailed to the pole at a later time. It may be that there were two poles though. This is not likely.  Niblack says: "Grave of Chief Shustocks on Shustock's Point, opposite Wrangell. Pole is surmounted by black bear." It is in front of a square house with a high platformed square under the roof.  Pole bought by Terr. Museum, Juneau from Rasmussen's estate - Oct. 1945.
Subjects: Totem poles--Alaska--Wrangell; Tlingit Indians--Structures

Title: Quinault graveyard across the Quinault River from Taholah, Washington, probably 1885
Notes: From unidentified material:  Indian graveyard across the river from the village of Quinault (now renamed Taholah). In the large ocean-going canoe are the remains of eight brothers and sisters out of one family. When an Indian died and before the corpse was cold a rope was put under the knees and around the back of the neck by which means the body was drawn up and tied in as small a bundle as possible. All belongings of the deceased were placed in and on the grave to be used in the happy hunting grounds.    PH Coll 568.9

Title: Kwakiutl village at Fort Rupert, British Columbia, 1914
Notes: Houses and totem poles.  This village of Tsahi was founded in 1840 when the tribe abandoned Kalokwis on Turnour Island in order to be near the Hudson's Bay Company post which was being established at Fort Rupert on Vancouver Island.  The totem pole in the foreground commemorates the legendary history of a Tsimshian family.  Its presence in this Kwakiutl settlement is due to the following circumstances.  A party of Seattle men, cruising in Alaska, innocently removed a totem pole from what they supposed was an abandoned village, and placed it in a public square of their city.  In reality the inhabitants of the Alaskan village were only temporarily absent, and when they returned and learned of the spoliation, there was a protest.  The news finally reached Fort Rupert where there lived a prominent member of the wronged family, the aged Tsimshian widow of a former employee of the Hudson's Bay Company.  In order to wipe out the stain on the family name, she had a local carver produce a totem pole according to her description of the lost one.  She had it erected at the house of her eldest son's eldest son.  According to Viola Garfield, the original pole was stolen from Tongass, Alaska and placed in Pioneer Square in 1899, making it of Tlingit manufacture.      Caption on mount: Qagyuhl                        village at Fort Rupert    Image from: Edward Curtis'     Native American Indian, Folio. v.10, pl. 353
Subjects: Kwakiutl Indians--Structures; Kwakiutl Indians--Arts &     crafts; Totem poles--British Columbia--Fort Rupert

Note from Museum of History and Industry: The totem pole at Pioneer Square has been a Seattle landmark since 1899. That year, a group of Seattle businessmen visited a Tlingit village in Alaska. They thought the village was deserted and removed a 50-foot tall  totem pole as a souvenir. The men brought the pole back to Seattle and had it set up in Pioneer Square. They were later fined for the theft of the pole. After being damaged by fire in 1938, it was replaced by a duplicate pole carved by Tlingit craftsmen.
